column168: PACKAGE WAS NOTICED LEAKING FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM WHILE ON THE VEHICLE FOR DELIVERY.  BOTTOM AREA OF DRUM APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN DENTED/CRUSHED SLIGHTLY CAUSING THE LEAK.  RECIPIENT REFUSED AND SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN 1A2 SALVAGE DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

THIS PACKAGE SPILL HAPPENED JUST AS THE SORT BEGAN IN MEMPHIS.  A SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST FROM THE DANGEROUS GOODS DEPT CLEANED UP THE SPILL PER FEDEX POLICY.  THIS PACKAGE WILL BE HELD UNTIL THE SHIPPER CLEARS THIS BY GIVING US FINAL DISPOSITION.

THIS SPILL OCCURRED IN THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER.  IT WAS CLEANED UP BY ONE OF THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALISTS PER FEDEX POLICIES.  THIS PACKAGE WILL BE HELD IN A SECURE AREA UNTIL THE SHIPPERS PROVIDES DISPOSITION INFORMATION.

THIS SPILL HAPPENED AT THE END OF THE SORT IN THE FEDEX MEMPHIS SORT FACILITY.  ONE OF THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALISTS TOOK CARE OF THIS SPILL PER FEDEX POLICY GUIDELINES.  THIS WAS PLACED IN A SAFE AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION INFORMATION FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO PAILS WERE DISCOVERED CRUSHED BY HEAVY TOP FREIGHT.  THE PAILS WERE RECOUPED INTO DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS WITH CHEMICAL LINERS, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SPILLAGE HAD EVAPORATED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND 22:50 TO A LEAKER IN UNLOAD DOOR 10. WEARING FULL PPE I FOUND A 5 PART HAZ-MAT WITH A STAIN IN CORNER. CONSULTED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SPILL TUB AND REMOVED TO HAZ-MAT REWRAP AREA.  INSPECTION SHOWED 2 OF 2 PLASTIC JUGS LEAKED DUE TO LOOSE CAP.  PRODUCT WAS REPACKED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. column168: ANOTHER VEHICLE BACKED INTO THE HOSE WHILE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING. COUPLING CAME LOOSE AND APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED BY DRIVER.  NO FURTHER INCIDENTS REPORTED.

PASCHALL DRIVER WAS PICKING UP A LOAD OFF THE DROP LOT.  BEFORE MOVING HE DID A WALK AROUND INSPECTION AND OPENED THE TRAILER TO MAKE SURE EVERYTHING WAS OKAY AND IT WAS BRACED.  HE DISCOVERED THAT THE BACK PALLET HAD SLID FORWARD AND (9) 15 GALLON PAILS HAD FALLEN OFF THE PALLET ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE PAILS ONLY HAD 1 LAYER AROUND THE PAILS OF SHRINK WRAP TO SECURE THEM TOGETHER, BUT NO SECUREMENT TO THE PALLET.  (1) PAIL LEAKED AROUND THE SEAL ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  EMI WAS CONTACTED AND FOSS CLEAN-UP COMPANY CAME OUT AND TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN-UP.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. HAD NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL UNTIL THE CLEAN-UP CREW COULD ARRIVE.  FOSS WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DISPOSAL AND AFTER THE CLEAN-UP PTL WAS RELOADED, SHRINK WRAPPED AND LOAD LOCKS APPLIED BEFORE CONTINUING ON TO DESTINATION POINT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: 1 PALLET WEIGHING 305LBS, WAS NOT BLOCKED OR BRACED AT THE TIME OF LOADING.  THE PALLET IN QUESTION SHIFTED AND FELL ON TOP OF THE DRUM,  PUNCHERING THE METAL.  UPON DISCOVERY, CONWAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND THE SHIPPERS EMERGENCY ONTACTS WERE CONTACTED.  THE DRUM WAS CONTAINED IN A 95 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM, AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPING ORIGIN AS INSTRUCTED BY THE EMERGENCY CONTACT.  A FULL REPORT OF THE INCIDENT HAS BEEN FILED WITH OUR SAFETY DEPT. REGIONAL MANAGER, AS WELAS THE LOCATION THAT CAUSED THE INCIDENT.

THE DEWAR WAS MARKED AND LABELED FOR NITROGEN, REFRIGERATIED LIQUID, BUT THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX AND THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S DECLARATION WITH THE SHIPMENT. LOCAL FAA/CAFSO WAS NOTIFIED. PACKAGE HELD AT LOCATION PENDING COMPLETION OF FAA INVESTIGATION.

STRONG ODOR NOTICED DURING PACKAGE SORT OPERATION, INSPECTION REVEALED AIRCRAFT PART WITH WHAT IS BELIEVED TO BE JET A RESIDUE. THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, AND THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S DECLARATION WITH THE SHIPMENT. LOCAL FAA/CAFSO WAS NOTIFIED. PACKAGE WAS HELD AT LOCATION PENDING COMPLETION OF FAA INVESTIGATION.

THE METHOD OF TRANSFER WAS BY METERED PUMP AND THE EMPLOYEE WAS STANDING NEXT TO THE PUMP BUT LOST HIS FOCUS AND OVERFILLED THE TRAILER. MOST OF THE SPILLAGE WAS CAUGHT BY A DRIP BUCKET.
UNLOADING ON CUSTOMERS PROPERTY.  TANK WAS OVERFILLED.  MATERIAL SPILLED OVER TOP OF TANK.

column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED SPILL FROM PACKAGES AT RECEIVER DURING UNLOADING. THE PACKAGES RIPPED ALONG THE BOTTOM RAIL OF THE TRAILER.  THE RECEIVER CLEANED THE SPILL AND ACCEPTED ALL PRODUCT.

WHEN DRIVER STOPPED FOR MEAL HE NOTICED A LITTLE DRIP OUT OF BOTTOM OF TRAILER.  HE CALLED DISPATCHER TO ADVISE OF SITUATION.  FIRE DEPT, CHEMTREC & HAZMAT WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  UPON ARRIVAL FIRE DEPT PUT FLOOR DRY ON GROUND & THEY GOT A PLASTIC DRUM TO CATCH DRIP INTO.  ANOTHER TRUCKING COMPANY WAS LINED UP TO OFF LOAD UNTO & CONTINUE TRIP.  INSURANCE COMPANY ADJUSTER & OFFICIALS WERE ON SCENE.  ECI FROM ROCKFORD, FL WERE BROUGHT IN AS ENVIRONMENTAL PEOPLE TO CLEAN UP.  FLOOR DRY & DISPOSAL OF LEGALLY.  NO PRODUCT WENT TO DIRT OR ANY STORM SEWERS.

HE MOVED TOTE TO MIDDLE OF YARD AWAY FROM BUILDING & OTHER PRODUCT.  TOTAL 330 GALLONS DISCHARGED ONTO LIME STONE YARD.  AFTER DRIVER BUILT DIKE FROM SOD BICARB TO PROTECT BUILDING, HE WENT BACK WHERE THE TOTE HAD ORIGINALLY BEEN PLACED & FOUND THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE GROUND.  TRUCK FROM HOME OFFICE CARRIED WITH SODA ASH & SAVED FOR NEUTRALIZATER.  USED TWO 30 YARD TRUCK LOADS OF LINE STONE TO COMPLETE NEUTRALIZATION.

I THEN FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  I ISOLATED THE SPILL, I DISPOSED OF THE CONTAMINATED ITEMS VIA & HE DMP PROCESS.  I THEN DECONTAMINATED MY P.P.E.

UNLOADERS OPENED TRAILER DOOR AND SAW PACKAGE LEAKING.  HAZ - MAT RESPONDER PUT ON PPE AND CONTAINED LEAKING/SOILED PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TUB.  THE SAID PACKAGE HAD ALSO LEAKED ONTO THE BOX UNDERNEATH IT, HOWEVER, THIS BOX WAS NUMBER 2 OF 2 IN SHIPMENT SO BOTH WERE PUT INTO LINED SPILL TUBS.  LATER CONTENTS WERE SOLIDIFIED AND 2ND PKG.  EXAMINED.  THE CARTERTS OF THIS 2ND PKG HAD BEEN FOUND TO BE CONTAMINATED AND MADE READY FOR DMP.  AFTER DISPOSAL PROCEDURE PPE WERE AE-CONTAMINATED AND PAPERWORK COMPLETED.
BAGS WERE TORN OPEN WHEN TRAILER DOOR OPENED AT JACKSONVILLE DOCK. APPEARS DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.
SHIPMENT WAS PUNCTURED AT TIME OF UNLOADING OF TRAILER.  FORKLIFT DAMAGE.

A SHIPMENT OF 4 PLASTIC DRUMS WERE SHIPPED SHRINKED WRAPPED AND BANDED TOGETHER ON A SKID.  TWO OF THE PLASTIC DRUMS RUBBED TOGETHER WHILE IN TRANSIT UNIT A SMALL HOLE DEVELOPED IN ONE OF THEM CAUSING THE LEAKAGE.  LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED ON TRAILER FLOOR AND CLEANED UP. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A  RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT BACK TO SHIPPER.

THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT IS UNKNOWN.  THE PRO WAS OUT FOR DELIVERY ON 6-02-00, WITH A DRIVER SALES REP (DSR) WHO RESIGNED ON SAID DATE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND IN THE MORNING OF 06-06-00 IN OUR OS&D TRAILER.  THE DSR IS APPARENTLY RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INCIDENT.

column168: DOCK ASSOCIATE WAS UNLOADING PALLET, THE BOX FELL OFF THE PALLET. THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE DOCK AND PLACED IN THE YARD WITH THE TRAILER DOOR OPEN.  I ARRIVED TO THE TERMINAL, BACKED THE TRAILER TO THE DOCK AND UNLOADED THE BOX.  I THEN USED AN OVERPACKED (5 GALLON) FIBER DRUM AND PLACED THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE DRUM.  I THEN PUT ABSORBALL MATERIAL ON THE SPILL AND SWEPT IT UP.  I PLACED THAT ABSORBALL THAT WAS USED FOR CLEANUP IN A 5 GALLON PLASTIC PAIL FOR LATER DISPOSAL.  I TALKED TO THE ASSOCIATE WHO WAS INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT AND TOLD HIM TO BE MORE CAUTIOUS IN THE FUTURE.

THE LID ON THE CAN OPENED UP A LITTLE BIT TO, TO ALLOW SOME PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT.  THE BOX WAS PICKED UP AND PLACED ON THE GROUND WITH ARROWS POINTING UP. RECOUPED THE PACKAGE, AND CONTAINED THE MATERIAL.  THE DOCK ASSOCIATE CLEANED UP THE SMALL SPILL WITH ABSORBALL.  THE PRODUCT WAS GIVEN AWAY TO ONE OF OUR CUSTOMERS FOR FREE.  I TALKED TO THE ASSOCIATE AND EXPLAINED TO HIM TO BE MORE CAUTIOUS.

column168: TRACTOR TRAILER (TRANSPORT) WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HWY 46, CAME UPON A VEHICLE BACKING A UNLITED BOAT TRAILER ON ROADWAY, TRANSPORT SWERVED TO AVOID HITTING BOAT TRAILER BUT HIT BOAT TRAILER CAUSING TRANSPORT TO GO OFF ROAD, DOWN AN EMBANKMENT TRANSPORT ROLLED OVER SPILLING GASOLINE WHICH IGNITED BURNED CONTENTS AND TRACTOR TRAILER.

ASHLAND TRUCK BACKED INTO CUSTOMER'S DOCK (TEXTRON AUTOMOTIVE). WHILE TEXTRON EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING GAYLORD BOXES OF PLASTICS PELLETS, HE FORKED A DRUM OF PRIMARY AMYL ACETATE.  10-15 GALS LEAKED OUT OF DRUM.  TEXTRON CALLED IN PRO SERVICES TO CLEAN UP AND DISPOSE OF PARTIALLY FILLED DRUM.  ASHLAND CAN BILL TEXTRON FOR DRUM AND MATERIAL, SINCE THEIR EMPLOYEE CAUSED THE INCIDENT.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS ATTEMPTING TO OFF LOAD A SHORT CRATE WHICH HAD BEEN LOADED IN FRONT OF THE SHIPMENT OF DRUMS AT THE PREVIOUS TERMINAL.  THE OPERATOR FAILED TO COMPENSATE FOR THE LONGER BLADES GOING THROUGH THE CRATE AND OUT THE OTHER SIDE.  ONE OF THE BLADES STRUCK THE DRUM ON THE SIDE CLOSE TO THE BOTTOM WHICH PUNCTURED THE DRUM ALLOWING FOR THE LIQUID INSIDE TO ESCAPE.  A RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR RECEIVED COUNSELING FROM THE DOCK SUPERVISOR AND WILL BE REQUIRED TO TAKE REMEDIAL FORKLIFT TRAINING.

CARTON OF CORROSIVE PRODUCT WAS PART OF A PALLETIZED SHIPMENT WHICH HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE DOCK AT THE LOADING DOOR.  AT SOMETIME SOMEONE DOCKED A SHORT PALLET OF FREIGHT IN FRONT OF THE PALLET CONTAINING THE CORROSIVE PRODUCT.  THE FORKLIFT BLADE APPARENTLY EXTENDED BEYOND THE SHORT PALLET AND WHEN IT WAS DOCKED THE BLADE PUNCTURED THE CORROSIVE CARTON.  DAMAGED CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  FORKLIFT OPERATORS MUST ALWAYS BE AWARE OF THE TYPE OF FREIGHT THEY ARE HANDLING AND GUARD AGAINST FORKLIFT BLADES EXTENDING BEYOND PALLETS.

DRIVER/CONSIGNEE FOUND ONE PACKAGE WITH LOOSE CAP.  LOST APPROX 1/2- 1 GALLON DURING TRANSPORTATION.  SPILL CONTAINED ON PALLET CARDBOARD. CONSIGNEE UNLOADED 2 SKIDS OFF THE DRIVER'S TRUCK AND REALIZED THAT ONE OF SKIDS WAS WET ON THE BOTTOM, SO THEY RELOADED IT BACK ONTO THE DRIVER'S TRUCK. THE SKID CONSISTED OF DOUBLE STACKED 5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS FILLED W/ CORROSIVE LIQUID. THE PALLET WAS WET AND THERE WAS DRIED DRIPPINGS DOWN THE SIDES OF TWO CONTAINERS. CONSIGNEE REFUSED TO ACCEPT THE FREIGHT. CALLED ECS FOR A CLEAN UP COMPANY- FEN VAC - CAME OUT TO FIND OUT THAT 1 OF THE CONTAINER'S SCREW ON LIDS WAS NOT ON PROPERLY AND WHEN THEY SHOOK THE CONTAINER BACK AND FORTH LIQUID SPILL OVER THE SIDES OF THE CONTAINER AND DRIPPED DOWN ON THE CONTAINER BELOW. FEN VAC IS GOING TO OVERPACK THE 1 CONTAINER AND DISPOSE OF IT ALONG WITH THE SKID AND CARDBOARD THAT WAS UNDER THE CONTAINERS.

column168: 1 CARDBOARD PACKAGE CONTAINING 12 1 QUART CANS WAS DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  IT WAS SENT TO THE CON-WAY SOUTHERN TERMINAL IN ATLANTA GEORGIA FROM THE DENVER COLORADO TERMINAL.  IT WAS LOADED ONTO THE REAR OF AN C.R.  ENGLAND TRAILER #10194.  WHEN THE TRAILER ARRIVED AT THE ATLANTA TERMINAL AND THE DOORS OPENED IT WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER.  THE OCCURED AT DOOR#137 OF THE ATLANTA TERMINAL.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT FOUR OF THE QUART CANS WERE DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THE ENTIRE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE.

PASCHALL DRIVER WAS A SLEEP IN TRUCKSTOP WHEN HE WAS AWAKEN BY ANOTHER DRIVER TO TELL HIM HE HAD PRODUCT LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER. HE CALLED THE FIRE DEPT., TOLD THE TRUCKSTOP AND NOTIFIED THE POLICE.  THE LA. STATE POLICE HM REPORTING LINE WAS ALSO CALLED AND NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE THE T/S, 2 MOTELS AND A CONVENIENCE STORE WHERE ALL EVACUATED.  OUR INSURANCE CARRIER WAS NOTIFIED AND A ADJUSTOR WAS SENT TO THE SCENE.  EM I WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY CONTRACTED RV-BARK ENVIRONMENTAL OUT OF JEFFERSON, LA.  TO DO THE CLEAN-UP.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED TO OBTAIN A MSDS SHEET.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE CLEAN-UP CREW, THE LAST 55 GALLON DRUM ON THE LOAD WAS LEAKING.  IT HAD A SMALL PIN HOLE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE LOAD WAS STILL BLOCKED AND BRACED AND NOTHING HAD TURNED OVER.  THE CLEAN-UP CREW ESTIMATED MAYBE 2 GALLONS HAD SPILLED OUT. While at the consignee's location, the driver noticed a leak in the trailer and returned to the terminal for investigation and cleanup. One wet carton containing sixty, sixteen-ounce plastic bottles was discovered. An undetermined number of bottles were damaged and all were affected. Approximately 1 gallon of free product was released. The free product was contained inside the carton and on the shrink-wrap. The terminal hazmat team used level C PPE to enter the trailer and placed the wet carton, it's contents, and the shrink-wrap into a thirty gallon fiber recoup drum. The recoup drum will be held at the terminal for disposition. The remainder of the shipment is being held at the terminal awaiting instructions from the shipper. There were no injuries or exposures reported. The MSDS was requested and received.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: While unloading, two, damaged, 5-gallon pails were discovered in the rear of the trailer. Approximately eight ounces of free product were released. Apparently the damage to the pails was due to the load shifting. The terminal hazmat team performed the clean-up using level D protection and absorbent material. The two damaged pails were each placed into a 10-gallon overpack drum. Both of the overpack drums will be forwarded to the consignee. The clean-up material were placed into a 10 gallon fiber recover drum. The recovery drum will be held at the terminal for disposition. The two pails were the only pieces in the shipment. No injuries or exposures were reported. The MSDS was requested nd received.

During a routine inspection of the terminal, a dock worker discovered one damaged, five gallon pail. Upon further investigation it was discovered, five additional pails were affected. Approximately four gallons of free product were released. Apparently the damage to the pail was due to be puncture by a forklift. The terminal Hazmat team performed the cleanup using level D protection and amphomag. The cleanup materials and damaged five gallon pail were placed into two, ten gallon metal recovery drums. The recovery drums will be held at the terminal for disposition. The five affected drums were wiped off and will be held at the terminal with the remainder of the shipment awaiting consignee instructions. No injuries or exposures were reported. The MSDS was requested and received.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON SATE ROUTE 2, ABOUT THREE MILES SOUTH OF BELMONT, WEST VIRGINIA, APPARENTLY THE TRACTOR-TRAILER BLEW OUT A TIRE CAUSING THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT TO JACKKNIFE. A 5-GALLON PAIL WAS DAMAGED INSIDE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 5-GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO BEING CRUSHED BY A TOTE BIN AS A RESULT OF THE LOAD SHIFTING. THE SHIPPER'S HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP. THE SHIPPER'S HAZMAT TEAM RETURNED THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE SHIPPER. THE THREE PAILS WERE UNAFFECTED. THE BELMONT FIRE DEPARTMENT, WEST VIRGINIA STATE HIGHWAY PATROL, CYTEC EMERGENCY SERVICES, AND THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION OUT OF CHARLESTON, WEST VIRGINIA WERE ON SCENE.  NO SOIL OR WATER WERE AFFECTED. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DOCK WORKER DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE 5 GALLON METAL PAIL WAS FOUND DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE LIQUID WAS RELEASED AND DRIED TO THE SID OF THE SHIPPING CONTAINER. APPARENTLY THE PAIL WAS DAMAGED IN TRANSIT BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. CLEAN UP WAS NOT INITIATED. THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS RE-STACKED IN THE TRAILER AND HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. AN MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING, FIVE GALLON PAIL WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE PAIL WAS LEAKING DUE TO A LOOSE LID. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION. ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZERS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. THE ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZER AND THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON POLY DRUM.  THE POLY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING PAIL WAS WIPED OFF, THE LID WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE PAIL WAS FORWARDED TO  THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: WHILE LOADING AT THE TERMINAL, A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT DRUM CARRIER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 20 GALLON FIBER DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS TIPPED, PLUGGED AND PLACED INTO A 65 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT. THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. AN MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, THREE WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR ONE-GALLON METAL PAILS, WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFMARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGED AND SEVEN WERE AFFECTED.  THE THIRD CARTON WAS NOT OPENED, AS THERE WAS ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON IT. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A SKID DURING LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PPE AND ABSORBENT TOWELS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND TWO WET CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE SEVEN AFFECTED PAILS WERE CLEANED OFF AND RECOUPED, THE THIRD CARTON WAS CLEANED OFF, AND ALL WERE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING A DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING ONE, GALLON METAL CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS A RESULT OF PACKAGE FAILURE. APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE FREE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED BY THE CARDBOARD PACKAGE. THE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED IN THE THIRD QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER, PACKAGING AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT. MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE CARTON CONTAINING TWO, 5 AND 1/2 POUND GLASS CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT BOTH GLASS CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER WAS DUE TO BEING DROPPED IN HANDLING., THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZER. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE WET CARTON AND THE TWO DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A 35 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE 35 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. ONE EMPLOPYEE WAS HOSPITALIZED DUE TO AN EXPOSURE. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED FIFTY-SIX POUND BAGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B PPE, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACE INTO A 45 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Burst or Ruptured
column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUG IN A CARTON OF FOUR PLASTIC JUGS, WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED AT THE THREE QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PLASTIC JUG WAS DUE TO PACKAGING FAILURE. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZER AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS, THE DAMAGED JUG AND THE DAMAGED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A 5 GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THREE REMAINING JUGS FROM THE CARTON WERE RE-BOXED AND WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. AN MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE LOADING, 24, FIVE GALLON METAL PAILS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGED AND THE OTHER 23 WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, AND DAMAGED PAIL WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE 23 UNAFFECTED PAILS WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE 55-GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A 55 GALLON DRUM OF PAINT WASTE CONTAINING METHYL ETHYL KETONE WAS BEING MOVED AT A 10 DAY STORAGE FACILITY. IN THE PROCESSES OF BEING MOVED, THE DRUM WAS TILTED AND 4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL SPILLED OUT OF THE TOP. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE DRUM WAS OVER PACKED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 POUND OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE PICKUP WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

WHEN A SAFETY -KLEEN DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS FACILITY, HE OPEN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND DISCOVERED A 16 GALLON DRUM OF CORROSIVE CLEANING COMPOUND HAD FELL OVER SPILLING 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL. ONE GALLON SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PARKING LOT AND THE OTHER 4 GALLONS WAS CAPTURED IN THE TRUCK'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE SPILL IN THE TRUCK AND THE PARKING LOT WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 50 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 130-A FRONTAGE ROAD IN LEXINGTON, VA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM SECUREMENT PROCEDURES FOR TRANSPORTATION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.
NO REMARKS

CUSTOMER'S FITTING WAS A CAMLOCK AND OUR ACID HOSE IS A 4-BOLT FLANGE FITTING. THE CONSIGNEE MADE A FITTING TO ADAPT TO OUR FLANGE FITTING. WHILE UNLOADING, THE MADE-UP FITTING CAME APART CAUSING A LOSS OF 5 TO 10 GALS. OF PRODUCT. OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND THE CONSIGNEE REPAIRED THE FITTING AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT FOR DISPOSAL.
DRUM FELL OFF PALLET WHILE BEING MOVED BY FORKLIFT.  THE TOP CAME LOOSE FROM THE DRUM.  THE SPILLED CONTENTS WERE RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND SENT TO DESTINATION.
A CARTON WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED BY HEAVIER MATERIAL STACKED ON TOP. A VERY SMALL AMOUNT WAS SPILLED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

FARMERS ELEVATOR COMPANY'S VEHICLE WAS HEADED NORTH ON STATE ROAD 3 AROUND 700 SOUTH PULLING 2 ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. A PICK-UP ALSO HEADING NORTH ON STATE ROAD 3 STRUCK THE BACK TRAILER CAUSING THE CYLINDER TO COME OFF THE TRAILER AND ROLL INTO A BEAN FIELD.  THE SHUT OFF VALVE WAS BROKEN OFF AND WAS ALLOWING AMMONIA TO LEAK OUT.  FARMERS ELEVATOR'S EMPLOYEE THEN RADIOED THE ELEVATOR TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT AT WHICH TIME TIM HERD CALLED 911. THEN A TRAINED EMPLOYEE WENT TO THE SCENE AND SHUT THE LEAKING VALVE AND STOPPED THE LEAK. WE HAVE TRAINING EVERY YEAR ON HAULING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO PREPARE OUR EMPLOYEE'S FOR ACCIDENTS AND THE PROCEDURES IN HANDLING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.

column168: THE LOWER LOAD LOCK AT REAR OF TRAILER FAILED. THIS FAILURE ALLOWED STACKED FIBERBOARD BOX'S OF REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE (RMW) TO SHIFT DURING TRANSPORT. DUE TO THE LENGTH OF THE TRANSPORT THE UNCONSTRAINED SHIFTING OF INDIVIDUAL BOX'S CRUSHED THE OUTER BOX'S AND IN SOME CASES CREATED TEARS IN THE INNER LINING. UPON OPENING DOORS FOR UNLOADING OF RMW THE PLANT PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND NOTIFIED THEIR SUPERVISOR. A SURVEY OF THE DAMAGE WAS ACCOMPLISHED AND APPROPRIATE SPILL RESPONSE WAS INITIATED BY THE PLANT PERSONNEL. RECOMMENDATION TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES OF THIS NATURE WOULD BE TO HAVE A DOUBLE CHECK OF THE LOAD LOCKS- ONE BY THE LOADING PLANT PERSONNEL AND ONE BY THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE DRIVER.

column168: UNIT # 1 TRAVELING E ON I 82 MP 1 X C  APPROX 28 MPH  WHEN REAR ENDED BY UNIT # 2.  UNIT # 1'S TANK RUPTURED AND PRODUCT CAUGHT FIRE.  SMALL BRUSH FIRE STARTED AS WELL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THIS FREIGHT CONSISTED OF 5 PALLETS CONTAINING 200 BAGS.  WHILE DELIVERING THE DRIVER NOTICED SOME POWDER ON THE FLOOR OF HIS TRAILER COMING FROM A BAG ON THE BOTTOM OF A PALLET.  THIS PALLET WAS NEXT TO WHERE ANOTHER PALLET OF BAGS HAD JUST BEEN REMOVED BY UNLOADER AT CONSIGNEE.  DRIVER WAS NOT SURE IF DAMAGED WAS CAUSED BY OUR LOADER WHEN TRAILER WAS INITIALLY LOADED AT TERMINAL THAT MORNING, OR IF UNLOADED CAUSED IT WHEN HE UNLOADED PALLET BESIDE IT. DAMAGED BAG WAS REMOVED AND PLACED IN SALVAGE CONTAINER ALONG WITH SPILLED MATERIAL AND WAS RETURNED TO OUR FACILITY AWAITING DISPOSITION.  BAGS ALWAYS SEEM TO CAUSE A PROBLEM IN THE TRUCKING INDUSTRY, WE TRY TO PLACE AS MUCH DUNNAGE AROUND THEM TO TRY AND ELIMINATE THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE.  MAYBE IF MORE DUNNAGE HAD BEEN USED THIS RELEASE WOULD OR COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: DELIVERY DRIVER WAS DELIVERING THIS SHIPMENT TO CONSIGNEE ON ORIGINAL STRETCH WRAPPED PALLET PICKED UP FROM SHIPPER THE DAY BEFORE.  WHILE BEING UNLOADED, THE UNLOADER NOTICED A SMALL PIN HOLE LEAK AT THE TOP CHIME OF DRUM.  CONSIGNEE ASSISTED DRIVER IN PLACING IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED. THERE WAS NO APPARENT ACTION THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THIS FAILURE, OUR CONCLUSION WAS THAT IT WAS DEFECTIVE DRUM - BAD TO CHIME.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS MOVING FREIGHT ACROSS THE DOCK AND STRUCK SAID DRUM THAT  WAS STAGED ON THE DOCK WITH THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT. DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON SIDE AND SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH DAMAGED DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS GIVING WARNING AND TOLD TO PAY ATTENTION TO JOB AT HAND AND THE SERIOUSNESS OF HIS UNATTENTIVENESS.

UNLOADER WAS UNLOADING A LINEHAUL TRUCK FROM SOUTHEASTERN FREIGHT LINES AND CAME ACROSS A PALLET OF BAGS THAT WAS LEAKING.  APPARENTLY THERE WAS ONE BAG ON THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET THAT WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER PALLET OF FREIGHT RUPTURING ONE BAG ON THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET.  DAMAGED BAG AND SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND SHIPPED ALONG WITH OTHER FREIGHT TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.  MAYBE IF DUNNAGE HAD BEEN PLACED IN BETWEEN PALLETS THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED.

DRUM WAS BEING UNLOADED AND DOCKWORKER NOTICED SMALL SEEPAGE AROUND 2' BUNG WHILE UNLOADING IT.  TRIED TO TIGHTEN WITH A BUNG WRENCH BUT WAS AS TIGHT AS IT COULD GET AND STILL PROCEEDED TO LEAK.  PLACED DRUM IN A POLY SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  APPEARS THAT IT WAS A DEFECTIVE BUNG CAP.

DELIVERY DRIVER WAS DELIVERING THIS FREIGHT AT CUSTOMER AND UPON UNLOADING FOUND ONE PAIL SLIGHTLY LEAKING AT REMOVABLE LID. APPARENTLY IT WAS HIT BY OTHER FREIGHT WHEN LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER SLIGHTLY DENTING TOP OF PAIL AND RUPTURING SEAL AT LID.  DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHEN DELIVERING THIS IBC, CONSIGNEE NOTICED SMALL AMOUNT OF SEEPAGE AROUND TOP CLOSURE.  THE RING AROUND TOP CLOSURE WAS TIGHTENED AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE, HAZ/MAT ABSORBENT BOOM WAS PLACED AROUND CLOSURE, AND IBC WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE "O" RING ON TOP CLOSURE WAS PINCHED AND DEFECTIVE.

column168: DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK FROM THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 85 GALLONS OF ACID WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOTE, AFFECTING THE ROADWAY, THE TRAILER FLOOR AND A 50-FOOT SECTION OF DITCH.  THE PRODUCT OF THE ROADWAY WAS LEFT IN PLACE PER MODOT, DUE TO THE FACT THAT IT WAS A VERY SMALL QUANTITY, OVER A LARGE AREA  (A STRIP 2 1/2 FEET WIDE APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES LONG).  A 300-FOOT SECTION OF AFFECTED ROADWAY SHOULDER WAS COVERED WITH SODA ASH.  THE LARGEST AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS IN THE 50-FOOT SECTION OF DITCH.   THE PRODUCT IN THE DITCH WAS COVERED WITH SODA ASH.  ON 06/09/00 HMRI RETURNED TO THE SITE AND TILLED UP THE AFFECTED SOIL, AND ADDED WATER AND LIME UNTIL A PH BETWEEN 5.5 AND 6 WAS OBTAINED.  NO LASTING ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT WAS NOTICED OR IS EXPECTED. RELEASE:  IT IS UNKNOWN TO THE WRITER OF THIS REPORT WHAT CAUSED THE RELEASE.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THERE WAS A CRACK ON THE BOTTOM SIDE OF THE TOTE, BUT HMRI WAS UNABLE TO CONFIRM THAT BELIEF.  HCI CHEMTREC WILL TAKE A CLOSER LOOK AT THE TOTE AFTER IT HAS BEEN DECONED, AND DETERMINED THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  DISPOSAL: ANY WASTE GENERATED FROM THIS INCIDENT WILL BE HANDLED BY HCI CHEMTREC.

DRIVER DRIVING DOWN N. WATER STREET PASSED UNDER A RAILROAD VIADUCT WHICH COLLIDED WITH THE DOME LID ON TOP OF THE TRAILER.  ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. COVERED WITH SAND AND ABSORBENT PADS.  HMHTTC WAS CONTRACTED FOR CLEANUP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER WAS IN PROCESS OF PUMPING OFF A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL WHEN THE BOTTOM OF THE HOSE ON THE PUMP COME OFF.  (THE EARS IN COMELOCK FITTING VIBERATED LOOSE.)  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF VALVES, BUT APPROX 60-80 GALLONS SPILLED.  DRIVER HAD NOT TIED DOWN EARS ON HOSE FITTING.  IF THE DRIVER HAD TIED THE EARS DOWN THE SPILL WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURED.  THE MINE PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND DISPOSED OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO UNLOAD HIS 8000 GALLON LOAD INTO AN EMPTY ABOVE GROUND 12000 GALLON STORAGE TANK, BY CONSIGNEE.  TANK DID NOT HAVE ANY TYPE OF GAUGE TO TELL HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS IN IT.  DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSES AND STARTED PUMPING OFF.  HE WAS HAVING PROBLEMS WITH THE GOVERNOR ON THE ENGINE AND WAS IN THE CAB OF THE TRUCK TRYING TO SOLVE THE PROBLEM.  WHEN THE TANK OVER FILLED SPILLING APPROX 400 GALLONS INTO A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA.  WHEN HE SAW THE OVERFILL, HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF VALVES AND PUMP.  HE THEN CALLED HIS TERMINAL MANAGER AND THEN INFORMED CONSIGNEE.  THEY CHECKED THE TANK AND FOUND A VALVE HAD BEEN SHUT OFF.  THE SUPPOSED EMPTY TANK WAS ALMOST FULL WHEN DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD.  THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OUT OF CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA AND AREA WAS CLEANED UP.  BECAUSE THERE WAS NO GAUGE ON THE TANK IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE FOR THE DRIVER TO KNOW HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS IN THE TANK.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

ACFX 89835 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ON SIDES OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, FERGUSON-HARBOUR INC, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE CAR LEAKING MATERIAL FROM THE MANWAY DUE TO OVERLOADING  AND HEAT EXPANSION OF THE PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT WAS REDUCED BY OFF-LOADING 1,000 GALLONS INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS AND THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED FOR FURTHER HANDLING.

ACFX 18608 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ODOR IN AREA OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES.  REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG SLOWING, BUT NOT STOPPING THE RELEASE.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER RAIL CAR FOR DELIVERY.  THE DEFECTIVE CAR WAS BAD ORDERED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIR TO THE DEFECTIVE VALVE.

column168: AT 16:00 HOURS ON 06-28-00 I WAS NOTIFIED BY A DOCK HAND THAT I HAD A POSSIBLE HAZ-MAT SPILL.  I CHECKED IT OUT.  I NOTICED A BOX THAT HAD A CORROSIVE, LABEL ON IT TORN OPEN WITH THE FOUR-ONE GALLON CONTAINERS BUSTED OPEN AND LAYING ON THE FLOOR.  I CHECKED THROUGH THE BILLS AND THE MANIFEST AND I COULD'NT FIND ANY THING.  I THEN LOOKED AT THE BUSTED BOX.  THERE WAS'NT AND PRO STICKERS OR LABELS ON THE BOX.  I DID GET THE HAZ-MAT INFORMATION ON THE BOX.  I THEN PULLED THE DOOR BACK DOWN, SECURED THE AREA, CHECKED THE ERG HANDBOOK AND THEN CALLED EDDIE YANCE WITH ALL THE INFORMATION I HAD. EDDIE YANCE COULD'NT HELP AND SUGGESTED I GET IN TOUCH WITH THE PHL TERMINAL TO SEE IF THEY COULD GIVE ME ANY TYPE OF INFORMATION.  I DID THIS.  THEY WERE UNABLE TO HELP.  I THEN GOT THE MANUFACTORS PHONE # FROM ONE OF THE BUSTED CONTAINERS.  (RECTOR SEAL- HOUSTON, TX) I TALKED WITH SCOTT KEY FROM THERE TECHNICAL DEPARTMENT.  I EXPLAINED TO HIM WHAT HAD OCCURED.  HE WAS ABLE TO SEND ME THE MSDS ON THE PRODUCT.  I THEN CALLED EDDIE YANCE BACK WITH THIS NEW INFORMATION.  I THEN FOLLOWED HIS INSTRUCTIONS

column168: TWO FIVE GALLON CONTAINERS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE LEAKED DURING TRANSIT FROM DURANT, OKLAHOMA CITY, OKLAHOMA.  CAUSE OF RELEASE IS CONTAINER FAILURE OF THE FIVE GALLON BUCKETS.  THEY HAD CRACKED ON BOTTOM AND WERE DISCOVERED THIS WAY.  BEAVER EXPRESS MOBILIZED E.M.I. TO CLEANUP THE LIQUID FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  E.M.I. UTILIZED ABSORBENT TO ABSORB THE LIQUID AND CONTAINERIZED THE WASTE INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED CARTON CARTON CONTAINING FOUR PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS WAS DAMAGED, AND AFFECTED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CARTON. APPROXIMATELY 3 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED INSIDE OF THE DAMAGED CARTON.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON WAS DUE TO THE FREIGHT SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TH THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A 5 GALLON PAIL WAS DAMAGED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT.  APPARENTLY THE PAIL WAS CRUSHED IN HANDLING.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED AT THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE 10 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE FORWARED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 30 GALLON AND A 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE 30 AND THE 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

FRANGIBLE DISC RUPTURED DUE TO POSSIBLE HYDRAULIC PRESSURE SURGES DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTERWARDS.

A LIQUID HYDROGEN TANKER WAS ON THE RETURN TRIP TO THE PACE, FL FACILITY AFTER MAKING A DELIVERY, THE TANKER WAS ESSENTIALLY EMPTY. HOWEVER, WHILE ON THE ROAD THE DRIVERS NOTICED AN INCREASE IN TRAILER PRESSURE.  PER PROCEDURE THEY NOTIFIED THE AIR PRODUCTS EQUIPMENT SUPPORT TEAM.  TO AVOID THE POSSIBILITY OF HAVING VENTS OPEN WHILE TRAVELING ON THE ROAD.  THEY WERE DIRECTED TO A TRUCK STOP EAST OF EL PASO, TX.  THERE THEY PERFORMED A CONTROLLED MANUAL VENTING OF THE TRAILER, FROM 45 PSIG TO 8 PSIG.  THEY THEN RETURNED TO PACE, FL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATOR OBSERVED THE RELEASE AT APPROXIMATELY 0830 AM CDT. WHICH WAS DUE TO A LOAD SHIFT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 11:02 AM CDT.  WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL  ARRIVED TO INITIATE REMEDIATION OF THE PHOSPHORIC ACID.  WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL USED A SODA ASH/CAUSTIC SODA/ WATER SOLUTION AND WAS APPLIED BY SCRUB BRUSHES TO NEUTRALIZE.  WEAVERTOWN SECURED THE LOAD WITH STRAPS TO PREVENT FURTHER LOAD SHIFTS.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING 250 GALLON TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THREE QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE LID.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEAN UP SUITS WERE PLACED INTO A FORTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LID ON THE TOTE WAS TIGHTENED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING 55-GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TEN OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND AMPHOMAG TO NEUTRALIZE THE AREA INVOLVED.  THE BUNG ON THE DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE 10-GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM, ONE 10-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, AND ONE 55-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, THREE WET CARTONS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  EACH CARTON CONTAINED SIX, ONE GALLON CONTAINERS. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE CONTAINER WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINDER WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY SIX OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO THE HAZ MAT SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION.  THE FREE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED BY THE CARTON.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER, CLEANUP MATERIALS AND WET CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. column168: WHEN UNLOADING WE FOUND THAT A BUNDLE OF STEEL HAD FALLEN IN TRANSIT PUNCTURING TWO CASES OF THE HAZARDOUS SHIPMENT.  AT THIS TIME I WAS NOTIFIED AND PROCEDED TO CLEAR THE AREA AND GET THE BILL OF LADING TO SEE WHAT WE WERE DEALING WITH.  AT THIS TIME I REALIZED IT WAS POISON, BUT NOT A INHALATION HAZARD.  I LOOKED INTO THE TRAILER TO SEE HOW LARGE OF A SPILL WE HAD AND THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR, SO I ADVISED EVERYONE TO STAY AWAY AND I CALLED CHEMTREC.  I WAS FAXED MSDS SHEETS AND GIVEN PROCEDURES TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP.  A LITTLE WHILE LATER MY SERVICE CENTER MANAGER ARRIVED AND MADE THE DECISION TO CALL IN A HAZMAT CLEANUP CREW.
DRIVER USED  FORKLIFT TO OPEN TRLR DOOR JABBED BOTTOM OF DRUM WITH FORKBLADE.
DRUM WAS PIERCED BY FORK WHILE LOADING OTHER FRT. DIME SIZED HOLE WAS PLUGGED W/ PUTTY AND METAL TAPE.

IBC WAS DRAINED OF REMAINING PRODUCT AND SPILLED PRODUCT REMEDIATED AFTER LOAD TRANSFERRED INTO DIFFERENT TRAILER. MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL,  INC.  OF OAKLAND,  CALIFORNIA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL, INC.  WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WITH ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: I PULLED IN DRIVEWAY AND STOPPED BY PICKUP AND CAR AND WENT TO SEE WHERE THEY WANTED ME TO UNLOAD ACID I HAD TO BACKUP TO GET OVER SO I COULD MAKE TURN IN TO TANKS.  AS I WAS PACKING UP THERE WAS A PICK UP THAT COME IN TO DRIVEWAY.  I HAD TO HIT BRAKES HARD TO STOP.  I WAS BACKING DOWN A HILL AND I GOT A BAD SUNG OF PRODUCT WHEN I PULLED UP TO ACID TANK THE RECEIVER TOLD ME I HAD A DRIP OUT OF OVERFLOW HOSE.  I WENT UP ON TRAILER AND FOUND ONE WING NUT LOOSE ON DOME LID. GEAL WAS STILL ON LID DIST MANAGER FOR DSI CAME TO ME AND TOOK REPORT.  I WAS TO TAKE TRAILER 7428 BUT WHEN I GOT TO FMC THEY TOLD ME TO UNHOOK FROM 7428 AND TAKE 7426 ON TRIP AND THAT TRAILER WAS ALREADY LOADED.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0010 HOURS ON JUNE 17, 2000 OUR DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON US-85 AND HAD JUST CROSSED THE NORTH DAKOTA - SOUTH DAKOTA BORDER.  HE GOT TOO CLOSE TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY AND THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE VEHICLE LEFT THE PAVEMENT.  HE CORRECTED AND BROUGHT THE VEHICLE BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY.  HE FELT A BUMP AND WHEN HE LOOKED IN HIS MIRRORS HE SAW SPARKS.  THE "PUP", THE SECOND OF A TWO TRAILER COMBINATION, HAD COME LOOSE FROM THE MAIN TRAILER AND ROLLED OVER IN THE HIGHWAY.  THE DRIVER STOPPED HIS VEHICLE AND STARTED TO GO BACK TO THE PUP.  HE SAW THERE WAS A VAPOR CLOUD AROUND THE PUP AND HE COULD HEAR THE SOUND OF ESCAPING GAS.  RATHER THAN GO INTO THE GAS CLOUD HE PULLED HIS VEHICLE FURTHER DOWN THE ROAD AND CALLED 911 TO REPORT THE CRASH.  NORTH DAKOTA HIGHWAY PATROL UNITS AND FIRE UNITS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  WHEN THE EMERGENCY UNITS RESPONDED THEY INFORMED OUR DRIVER THERE WAS ANOTHER VEHICLE INVOLVED.  IT HAD COLLIDED WITH OUR PUP TRAILER.  THE EXACT SEQUENCE OF EVENTS IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.  SOMETIME DURING THE ROLLOVER AND COLLISION A VAPOR LINE WAS BROKEN OFF OF THE TRAILER AND WHEN IT TIPPED ONTO IT'S SIDE LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS WAS ALLOWED TO ESCAPE.  AS IT ESCAPED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE, IT FORMED A VAPOR CLOUD AND DISPERSED.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY FIRST RESPONDERS, THEY REMOVED THE BROKEN PIPE AND INSTALLED A PLUG IN THE OUTLET.

CASE OF HYDROCHLORIDE ACID  SOLUTION WAS LEFT ON DOCK TO IDENTIFY WHO THE CONSIGNEE WAS.  SOMEONE DROVE OVER BOX.  THE CONTENTS SLOWLY LEAKED OUT.  I NOTICED THE PRODUCT LEAKING AND CALLED KIM MARVIN CWX SAFETY MGR.  WHO THEN INSTRUCTED ME TO CALL CONSOLIDATED WASTE MGMT.

DRIVER RECEIVED THE OK TO UNLOAD AND AIR PRESSURE PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  AFTER DRIVER WAS UNLOADED THE RECEIVING SUPERVISOR INFORMED OUR DRIVER THE STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED INTO THE DIKE AREA.  THIS IS A DOUBLE TANK.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND PUMPED OUT.

DRIVER PICKED UP TRAILER AT OUR TERMINAL AND PROCEEDED TO WEIGH. UPON ARRIVAL AT SCALE HE NOTICED DRIPPING OUT OF SKIN OF INSULATED TRAILER.  THE FRONT COMPARTMENT WAS TRANSFERRED ALONG WITH THE OTHER TWO COMPARTMENTS AND AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY TERMINAL PERSONNEL. TRAILER WAS SENT FOR REPAIRS AND HYDROSTATIC TESTED.  NO LEAKS WERE FOUND.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LOADER COULD HAVE DRIPPED SOME PRODUCT IN THE DOME AREA, WASHED IT DOWN AND FAILED TO NOTIFY ANYONE.

ON 06/18/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 0500 HOURS, CN/IC TRAIN CREW NOTED VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR ACFX 95679 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID) WHILE MAKING A PICK UP IN THE CN/IC FULTON YARD, FULTON, KY. APPROPRAIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED AND THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED. SHIPPER'S HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND  NOTED THAT THE CAP GASKET TO THE EDUCATION TUBE WAS WORN.  NEW GASKET INSTALLED, VAPOR DISPERSION STOPPED.  TANK CAR DECONNED BY SHIPPER AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ON 06/06/00 AT  APPROXIMATELY 0630 HOURS, CN MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT NOTED VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR TILX 300307 (RESIDUE, LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS) WHILE COMPLETING INSPECTIONS IN THE CN/GTW BRISTOL YARD, FLINT MI. APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED. CN HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT THE GAUGING DEVICE PACKING NUT WAS LOOSE. NUT TIGHTENED, VAPOR DISPERSION STOPPED. TANK CAR RELEASED AT 0715 HOURS.

DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING TO CONSIGNEE. THE ROAD TO CONSIGNEE HAS LOTS OF HILLS AND CURVES. HIS PALLET JACK THAT WAS TIED TO THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER BROKE LOOSE AND ROLLED INTO THE SIDE OF THE FIBER DRUM, PUNCTURING THE DRUM. WHEN DISCOVERED A FEW MINUTES LATER, THE DRIVER TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. IN THE FUTURE THE DRIVER MUST MAKE SURE THAT THE PALLET JACK IS PROPERLY SECURED AT ALL TIMES.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: CONTENTS OF 1 55 GAL DRUM LEAKED INTO TRAILER- WHEN TRAILER UNLOADED & DRUM PULLED OFF IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM BOTTOM. BOTTOM APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PATCHED, WAS CRACKED.

DAMAGE CAUSED BY IMPROPER LOADING AND BRACING.  NO LOAD LOCKS WERE USED. ALSO JAMMED WITH FORK BLADES. AFTER THE DISCOVERY OF LEAKAGE, SALEM TERMINAL LAID DRUMS ON SIDE. AFTER RECEIVING SALVAGE DRUMS, SALEM PUT DAMAGED DRUMS IN SALVAGE DRUMS.
PUTTING SKID ON TOP OF DRUM THAT WENT WITH SAME SHIPMENT, THE FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE DRUM.

ON 06/06/00 AT 2115 HOURS, A CN/IC SWITCH CREW OBSERVED VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RCRX 1064 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID). THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES NOTIFIED. INSPECTION BY THE CN/IC HAZMAT AND SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM NOTES THAT TWO OF FOUR BOLTS ON THE EDUCTION TUBE FLANGE WERE NOT SECURE, THE TWO OTHER BOLTS WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT. BOLTS REPLACED AND FLANGE WAS SECURED. TANK CAR RELEASED AT 2240 HOURS.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: AT 0400 ON JUNE 29, 2000, I WAS NOTIFIED OF A RELEASE OF UNKNOWN TYPE MATERIAL OF UNIT TRAVELING ON RT322 E. UPON LEARNING THIS, MANIFESTS WERE OBTAINED AND A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR NOTIFIED. IN ADDITION, THE LOCAL EMERGENCY SERVICE WERE NOTIFIED, COUNTY OFFICIALS, DEP AND OTHER AGENCIES THROUGH THE SPILL CENTER, INC. UPON ARRIVING ON SCENE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IT WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED THROUGH ASHLAND. MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY CONTRACTOR. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DAMAGE WAS THE RESULT OF A FORKLIFT MARK IN THE BOTTOM OF CONTAINER THAT LET LOOSE RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL. BETTER DUNNAGE AND OR INSPECTION OF THE MATERIAL WOULD PREVENT INCIDENTS SUCH AS THIS FROM OCCURRING.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: NO LOAD LOCKS WERE USED TO SECURE LOAD. THIS FAILURE ALLOWED STACKED REUSABLE PLASTIC DRUMS OF REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE (RMW) TO SHIFT DURING TRANSPORT. DUE TO THE LENGTH OF THE TRANSPORT THE UNCONSTRAINED SHIFTING OF INDIVIDUAL PLASTIC DRUM'S CAUSED LIDS TO DISLODGED FROM SPILLING REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE. UPON OPENING DOORS FOR UNLOADING OF RMW THE PLANT PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND NOTIFIED THEIR SUPERVISOR. A SURVEY OF THE DAMAGE WAS ACCOMPLISHED AND APPROPRIATE SPILL RESPONSE WAS INITIATED BY THE PLANT PERSONAL. RECOMMENDATION TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES OF THIS NATURE WOULD BE TO HAVE A DOUBLE CHECK OF THE LOAD LOCKS, BY PLANT PERSONNEL AND BY THE TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL.

GATX 94330 WAS REPORTED AS OVERLOADED AND INSPECTED BY AN FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OFFICER.  THE OFFICER FOUND LIQUID ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  CSXT HAZMAT PERSONNEL AND A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING ITEMS: VAPOR VALVE BLIND FLANGE HAD ALL FOUR BOLTS LOOSE, LIQUID VALVE SECUREMENT TO CAR LOOSE AND ONE BOLT STRIPPED, LIQUID VALVE GASKET DAMAGED, MANWAY GASKET THIN AND PRODUCT HAD COME THROUGH PACKING ON TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE FRA OFFICER HAD ALSO NOTED THAT TWO OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS LOOSE.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND PRODUCT WIPED OFF THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO A SECURE AREA AND 4000 GALLONS WERE TRANSFERRED TO A TRUCK.  A CONTRACTOR WAS SECURED  BY THE SHIPPER  TO REPAIR THE ITEMS NOTED.

GATX 63212, RES HYDROCHLORIC ACID, DISCOVERED VENTING VAPORS FROM THE TOP IN CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL.  E.G. COOK, HAZMAT MANAGER RESPONDED.  HE FOUND VAPORS COMING FROM THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY COVER.  HE INSPECTED THE RUPTURE DISK FOUND IT WAS NOT BLOWN.  HOWEVER, THE OUTER RING OF THE DISK WAS BADLY CRACKED AND DETERIORATED ALLOWING VAPORS TO VENT AROUND THE DISK.  THE DAMAGED DISK WAS REPLACED, THE COVER SECURED AND THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED.

WE IMMEDIATELY POURED ABSORBANT MATERIAL ON SPILL.  COAST OIL IS NOW CHECKING ALL FITTINGS FOR ANY DEFECTS OR ANY OTHER REASONS TO COMPROMISE THE SECURITY OF ANY CONNECTION TO ANY TANK OR OTHER FITTING.

DAMAGED CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR. FREIGHT LOADERS MUST ENSURE THAT HAZ MAT FREIGHT IS SECURE ON TRAILERS BEFORE TRANSPORT.

A DOCK WORKER WAS REMOVING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER. PICKED UP A SKID AND FOUND THE BOX UNDERNEATH THE PALLET. HE REMOVED THE PALLETS AND CHECKED OUT WHAT WAS LEAKING AND DISCOVERED THAT IT WAS HAZ MAT. HE THEN CAME UP AND TOLD ME AND WE CHECKED IN THE HAZ MAT BOOKS TO FIND OUT WHAT TO DO.  I CALLED CHEMTREC AND THEY FAXED THE INFORMATION WE NEEDED. WE THEN CLOSED DOWN THE DOOR AND STOPPED WORKING ON THE TRAILER. LATER ON, WE PULLED THE TRAILER OUT TO THE YARD.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: UPON UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER, TWO BOXES WERE WET ON TOP. OPENED THE TWO BOXES AND FOUND ONE BOTTLE IN EACH BOX LEAKING AT LID.  LOOSE LIDS WERE TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED LEAKAGE.  BOTTLES WERE RETURNED TO BOXES, RESEALED, AND SENT TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.

UNLOADER WAS UNLOADING THIS TRUCK WHEN HE CAME UPON THIS FREIGHT AND NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE UNDERNEATH IT.  HE BROKE THE PALLET DOWN AND FOUND TWO PAILS ON THE BOTTOM SLIGHTLY LEAKING.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO  SALVAGE CONTAINER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION THE FREIGHT LOOKS LIKE IT WAS SITTING OUTSIDE FOR SOME TIME...PAILS ARE RUSTY AND DIRTY.  JUST SEEMS THAT THE PAILS WERE FATIGUED AND CRACKED AT SEAMS WHILE IN TRANSIT.  THE FREIGHT WAS STRETCH-WRAPPED SO ORIGINAL P/U DRIVER DIDN'T NOTICE IT WHEN PICKING UP.  PERSONALLY, I QUESTION WHY THE SHIPPER WOULD EVEN SHIP THESE PAILS IN THIS CONDITION...BUT THAT IS JUST MY PERSONAL OBSERVATION.

DRIVER WAS MAKING ANOTHER DELIVERY AT A CUSTOMER.  WHEN CUSTOMER WAS REMOVING HIS FREIGHT WITH FORKLIFT HE STRUCK A PALLET OF BAGS WITH HIS FREIGHT RUPTURING 3 BAGS OF RESORCINOL.  DAMAGED BAGS AND SPILLED MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED. BAGS WERE ALWAYS CHALLENGING FOR TRUCKING COMPANIES, THEY CAN RUPTURE QUITE EASILY.  EVEN WHEN DUNNAGE IS PLACED AROUND THE PALLETS RELEASES CAN OCCUR LIKE MENTIONED ABOVED.  PERSONALLY, I FEEL THAT WHEN BAGS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARE TRANSPORTED, SHIPPERS SHOULD BE REQUIRED TO PLACE THE BAGS IN GAYLORD CONTAINERS OR SOMETHING OF THE SORT JUST TO ADD TO THAT EXTRA ADDED PROTECTION AND CONTAINMENT SHOULD THERE BE A RELEASE.  AGAIN, THAT IS MY OPINION.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, FORKLIFT OPERATOR STRUCK DRUM WITH OTHER FREIGHT PUNCTURING IT.  DRUM WAS TURNED OVER AND PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED. FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS TOLD TO PAY ATTENTION TO JOB AND BE ESPECIALLY CAREFUL AND CAUTIOUS WHEN WORKING AROUND AND NEAR DRUMS.

column168: OIL TRUCK TRAVELING SOUTH ON RT 7 WAS STRUCK IN THE REAR LEFT OUTSIDE WHEEL BY A VAN (NORTH) WHICH CROSSED OVER THE DOUBLE YELLOW LINE.  THIS PUT THE OIL TRUCK INTO A SKID WITH THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRUCK FACING SOUTH.  OIL TRUCK FLIPPED ONTO THE LEFT SIDE AND CONTINUED SKIDDING.  THE CAB OF THE OIL TRUCK STARTED STRIKING THE GUARD RAILS.  THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ON ITS TOP AS IT CAME TO A REST. (THE SKIDDING ON THE TRUCK'S LEFT SIDE CAUSED THE BAFFLE INSIDE THE TANK TO SEPARATE FROM A WELD) ONE OF THE GUARD RAIL I-BEAMS PUNCTURED THE FORWARD DOME LID ASSEMBLY, RELEASING THE OIL FROM THE TANK.  FUEL OIL MIGRATED DOWN A RIVER BANK AND INTO THE NORWALK RIVER.  FLEET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RECOVERED AT LEAST 2500 GALLONS TO DATE.

ON 06/19/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 0400 HOURS, CN/IC SWITCH CREW NOTED VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RCRX 1425 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID) AFTER SWITCHING SAME TO REST IN TRACK 10, CN/IC GEISMAR YARD, GEISMAR, LA.  APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED A RELEASE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEVE VALVE.  THE VALVE RESEATED AND WAS SECURE.  TANK CAR DECONNED WITH SOAP AND WATER, AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 0600 HOURS.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: ON 06/27/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 2115 HOURS, WHILE PERFORMING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE CN/IC GEISMAR YARD, GEISMAR, LA.  A CN/IC CONDUCTOR AND SWITCHMAN CAME IN CONTACT WITH VAPORS EMITTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 60788 (FORMALDEHYDE).  TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC AND SHIPPER'S HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT FIVE (5) OF SIX (6) MANWAY BOLTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  THE TEAM ALSO NOTED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS BROKEN.  GASKET REPLACED AND THE MANWAY SECURED.  TANK CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 0115 HOURS (06/28/00).  CONDUCTOR AND SWITCHMAN WERE TREATED AND RELEASED BACK TO WORK WITH NO RESTRICTIONS.

ON JUNE 21, 2000 A 55 GALLON 1A2/Y1.2/100/USA/-M4723/00/RL STEEL DRUM FAILED AT CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC'S.  (CHESI) FACILITY LOCATED AT 2930 INDEPENDENCE ROAD, CLEVELAND, OHIO 44115 CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  THE MATERIAL WAS WASTE, CAUSTIC ALKALI LIQUIDS N.O.S. (SODIUM HYDROXIDE/METASILICATE), 8, UN1719, PGII.  A TOTAL OF 16 DRUMS THAT WERE PACKAGED WITH THIS MATERIAL, HAVING HAD THE SAME UN RATING WERE IMMEDIATELY TRANSFERRED INTO PLASTIC DRUMS.  THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE WAS TO DO THE INCOMPATIBILITY OF THE MATERIAL WITH THE CONTAINER.  CHESI PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THAT ALL CONTAINERS THAT ARE TO BE FILLED WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS/WASTE, MUST BE COMPATIBLE WITH MATERIAL THAT IS BEING PLACED IN THE CONTAINER.

ON JUNE 12, 2000 AT APPROXIMATELY 14:00 CDT, AN ODOR COMPLAINT WAS FIELD WITH THE MONTGOMERY COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND NOTICED EMISSIONS FROM A TANKER. THE INCIDENT COMMANDER ON THE SCENE EVACUATED THE LOCAL CITGO STATION AND ADJACENT TANKERS ( APPROXIMATELY 7 PERSON) . THE DRIVER OF THE TANKER WAS ASLEEP INSIDE THE CAB. NO ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO WAKE THE DRIVER NOR OBTAIN THE SHIPPING PAPERS WITH EMERGENCY NUMBERS. AT APPROXIMATELY 15:00 CDT THE DRIVER AWOKE. LWD TRUCKING THEN CONTACTED THE 24 HOUR EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER AS LISTED ON THE MANIFEST. THE GENERATOR THEN CONTACTED THE EMERGERNCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE. THE MATERIAL HAD BEGAN AN EXOTHERMIC REACTION AND BUILT PRESSURE UNTIL THE PRESSURE VENT OPENED. THE GASKET DOME BEGAN TO VENT. ( CONT NEXT PAGE) CONTINUED FROM NUMBER IX : THE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE WERE ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE DOME AND STOP THE LEAK. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW CONTACTED BY THE TRANSPORTER ARRIVED ON SITE AND CLOSED THE PRESSURE VENT AND FURTHER TIGHTENED THE DOME. THERE WERENO FURTHER INCIDENTS WITH THE MATERIAL OR TANKER IN ROUTE TO THE DESIGNATED FACILITY. THE GENERATOR IS REVIEWING THE SAFETY OF TRANSPORTATION OF THE MATERIAL INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT.

column168: OUR DRIVER LEFT NASHVILLE ENROUTE TO DALLAS.  PRETRIP WAS MAKE AND NOTHING UNUSUAL WAS NOTED.  WHILE TRAVELING WEST ON I-40,  NEAR MILE-MARKER 144,  OUR DRIVER HEARD A LOUD EXPLOSION.  HE FIRST THOUGHT HE BLEW AT TIRE.  HE WAS PULLING OVER TO SIDE OF ROAD WHEN SOMEONE ON THE C.B. RADIO INFORMED HIM THAT REAR OF TRAILER HAD BLOWN OUT-SMOKE WAS VIABLE BUT NO FLAME.  OUR DRIVER TRAVELED 1 MILE TO EXIT 143-PULLED OVER AS FAR FROM ROADWAY AS POSSIBLE.  AFTER CHECKING ERG 2000 OUR DRIVER NOTED THAT TOXIC FUMES WOULD BE A POTENTIAL HAZARD.  OUR DRIVER UNHOOKED TRAILER & PULLED TO A SAFE DISTANCE.  FIRE DEPT, SHERIFF & FEMA WERE INVOLVED.  THE SHIPPER OF THE PRODUCT (BIX MANUFACTURING) DECIDED IS DRIVE TO SITE AND TO CONTACT THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTACT. 1 55 GALLON DRUM OF PAINT REMOVER HAD EXPLODED IN TRAILER. SECOND DRUM HAD EXPANDED AND APPEARED READY TO EXPLODE -  FERGUSON - HARBOR CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED & DECISION WAS MADE TO LET SECOND DRUM COOL BEFORE CLEAN UP COULD BEGIN - F.E.A REP. SAID NO SPILLAGE HAD OCCURRED SO HE FILED NO REPORT TO MY KNOWLEDGE- AFTER COOL DOWN CLEAN-UP WAS MADE ALL MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUMS AND TRAILER WAS BROUGHT BACK TO NASHVILLE,  TN. OWNER OF NIX  MANUF..  WAS ALSO AT SEEAN OF ACCIDENT FIRST NAME FRANK SORRY LOST HIS CARD. FIRE DEPT - TN HWY PATROL & CLEAN- UP CREW WERE PRESENT AT ALL TIMES UNTIL RELEASED TO RETURN TO NASHVILLE, TN. I HAVE NO IDEA WHAT CAUSED EXPLOSION BUT NO LEAKS OR FUMES WERE DISCOVERED DURING PRE-TRIP INSP,  ALSO  NO PLACARD REQUIRED ON HAZ-MAT ONLY (940LBS.) ALL INFO IS BEING SENT TO YOU HAVE ALREADY SENT PICTURES - PLS CONTACT FOR ANY MORE INFO.

THE TANK WAS CLOSE TO FULL (ABOUT 1-1.5 FEET BELOW THE TOP OF THE SIDE WALL OF THE TANK)  WHEN THE TRAILER EMPTIED. THE PIT CONTAINED THE DISCHARGE AND NONE ENTERED THE ENVIRONMENT. THE PIT WAS EMPTIED TO DETERMINE THE ACCURATE NUMBER OF GALLONS OF MATERIAL IN THE PIT.  WHEN ANALYZED,  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 353 GALLONS/546 POUNDS OF 100% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WAS IN THE PIT.  IT IS UNDETERMINED HOW MUCH WAS DUE TO THIS INCIDENT AND HOW MUCH WAS ALREADY IN THE PIT.

UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT BOTH ONE GALLON PAILS WERE DAMAGED AND THREE 16 -OUNCE BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED . THE REMAINING 21 BOTTLES WERE AFFECTED BUT NOT DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF TOTAL FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINERS WAS CAUSED BY A LOAD SHIFT DURING TRANSIT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS.THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, TWO WET CARTONS, TWO DAMAGED PAILS, AND THREE DAMAGED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE 21 AFFECTED BOTTLES WERE WIPED OFF, REPACKAGED,AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WILL THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, 1-GALLON CONTAINERS WAS DAMAGED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO OF THE CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED AND TWO WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY A HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP  USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS, AFFECTED CARTON, AND THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 30 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO UNAFFECTED CONTAINERS WERE RECOUPED INTO A CARDBOARD BOX AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO LEAKING 5- GALLON PAILS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE LIDS ON THE PAILS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVE C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55- GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSTITION. THE LIDS ON THE PAIL WERE TIGHTENED AND THE PAILS WILL BE  FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. column168: WHILE UNLOADING, THREE DAMAGED 50 POUND PAPER BAGS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1.25 POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCTS WERE RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BAGS WERE DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT BEING LOADED ON TOP OF THEM. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 15 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD  AT TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED PAPER BAGS WERE TAPED UP AND PLACED INTO HAZMAT  BAGS AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE . THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED FOUR, 55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS WERE DAMAGED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 2 CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT. APPARENTLY THE SEALS BECAME DAMAGED DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT BLANKETS. THE DRUM WERE RESEALED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 30 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE 30 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, FIVE WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, 16 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL TWENTY BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BOTTLES WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS , FREE PRODUCT , WET CARTONS, AND DAMAGED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THERE IS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED 55.1 POUND PAPER BAGS ON A SKID, WERE DISCOVERED AT THE THREE-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE- HALF POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE BAGS WERE PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT DURING LOADING. TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM SWEPT UP THE FREE PRODUCT USING LEVEL C PROTECTION. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT AND THE DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS RE - SKIDDED AND WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED . THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE MOVING THE TRAILER FROM THE YARD TO THE  DOCK TO BE UNLOADED, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A LEAK COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS LEAKING IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER H.M.H.T.T.C WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORMED THE CLEANUP . APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND SOME IMPACTED THE ASPHALT. THERE WERE NO SOIL OR WATER AFFECTED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE. THE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A 85 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS ALONG WITH THE REST OF THE MATERIAL WERE PLACED INTO 2, 55 GALLON OPEN HEAD RECOVERY DRUMS. BOTH 55 GALLON OPEN HEAD RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING , SEVEN , 55-GALLON DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE SEVEN LEAKING DRUMS WERE REPAIRED WITH PUTTY AND WILL FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 5- GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED TWO, 5 GALLON METAL CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED  RELEASING APPROXIMATELY .5 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT. APPARENTLY THE CONTAINERS WERE PUNCTURED DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING. THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED AT THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT BLANKETS. THE DAMAGED METAL CONTAINERS WERE EACH PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM THAT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION, THE DRIVER DETECTED AN ODOR AND ALERTED THE CONSIGNEE'S HAZMAT TEAM. UPON ENTERING THE TRAILER, THE CONSIGNEE'S HAZMAT TEAM DISCOVERED ONE DAMAGED, 5 GALLON METAL PAIL IN THE 1/2 WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1/2  A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND EVAPORATED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP BY PLACING THE DAMAGED PAIL INTO A 5 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS SENT BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND WILL HELD THERE UNTIL DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: R WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK AT HIS FACILITY WHEN HE DISCOVERED A LEAK FROM A PALLET OF SHRINK WRAPPED 1 GALLON CONTAINERS OF OIL-BASED PAINT. ON ONE OF THE CONTAINERS, THE LID POPPED OFF SPILLING THE PAINT ONTO THE TRUCK'S FLOOR. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 6125 N. PECATONICA ROAD, IN PECATONICA, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVERS WERE TRANSFERRING THE WASTE SOLVENT FROM A 15 GALLON STEEL DRUM TO A HOLDING TANK. THE SOLVENT WAS POURED INTO A SUMP WHICH IS THEN PUMPED TO THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE TOP OF THE TANK WAS CLOSED, SO THE 9 GALLONS OF WASTE SOLVENT SPILLED ALONG THE SIDE OF THE TANK INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED INTO A 30 GALLON METAL OPEN-TOP DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 110 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED , ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE IN HEBRON, OH FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER UNLOADING AND TRANSFERRING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: EXIT TAKEN AT FREEWAY SPEED, IN AN EFFORT TO SLOW DOWN OUR DRIVER APPLIED THE AIR BRAKES, THIS CAUSED THE MATERIAL IN THE TANKER TO "SURGE" AND MOVE FORWARD.  THE BRAKES WERE NO LONGER EFFECTIVE AND OUR DRIVER COULD NOT STOP THE VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE CONTINUED DOWN THE OFF RAMP WITHOUT STOPPING.  THE VEHICLE THEN CROSSED THE HWY LANES, OVER THE CURB,  CROSSED THE SIDE WALK.  CRASHING THROUGH A CHAIN LINK FENCE.  CLIMBED THE DIRT EMBANKMENT AND FINALLY ROLLED DOWN THE EMBANKMENT. SHE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING ITEMS: 4- FIBERBOARD BOXES EACH CONTAINING A 1 GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE NO POSITIVE MEANS OF CLOSURE, LABELED ANTI-FOG SILICONE LIQUID.  EACH CONTAINER LID WAS LOOSE WITH A TOTAL APPROXIMATE LOOSE OF PRODUCT AT 20OZ.  SHE REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX AND PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  SHE PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS THEN FORWARDED ON TO RECEIVER VIA GROUND TRANSPORTATION.  THE AREA  INVOLVED WITH THE LEAKAGE WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THERE WAS 1 EMPLOYEE INVOLVED WITH THIS LEAKAGE, SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED FOR THIS EMPLOYEE.  THE BOX WAS LABELED CONSUMER COMMODITY, ORM-D AND ORIENTATION ARROWS.  THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT AND WAS MOVED VIA GROUND TRANSPORTATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0228.

THIS SMALL LEAK/SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTERS SPILL CLEANUP GROUP.  THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND SPILL CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED PER FEDEX POLICY.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD IN A SECURE AREA UNTIL DISPOSITION INFORMATION IS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE OCCURRED.  THE CONTAINER WAS INADVERTENTLY TIPPED OVER IN HANDLING.  THIS ALLOWED THE LIQUID NITROGEN TO RELEASE FROM THE VENT HOLE AT THE TOP OF THE UNIT.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTRACTED FOR INSTRUCTIONS  AND THE CONTAINER WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

AS THIS SHIPMENT WAS BEING LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER, ANOTHER SKID WAS PUSHED AGAINST ONE OF THE DRUMS CAUSING A CRACK AND SOME SEEPAGE. THE DRUM WAS PLACED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
DRIVER COULD NOT CHECK THE GAUGE HE WAS TOLD TO DROP 2000 GALS SPILLED AT 1600 GALS.

column168: FILE 3001 D, SHPR:  TEXAS DEPT OF AGRICULTURE, AWB# AUS 8313318763 ELZ. ON 6/9/2000 AT 0102 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN THE HAZ MAT SORT LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS WILLIAM HENDERSON AND MARTIN CLINE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A "C" CONTAINER WHICH WAS EMITTING AN ODOR. UPON INVESTIGATION OF THIS CONTAINER, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX LABELED WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL, WHICH WAS THE CAUSE OF THE ODOR.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THERE INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES WHICH CONTAINED TWO GLASS 1 QUART BOTTLES.  ONE OF THE BOTTLES IN ONE OF THESE BOXES HAD A BROKEN LID.  ALL OF THE LIDS HAD TAPE ON THEM AS POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE, HOWEVER, THIS ONE FAILED.  THERE WERE CARDBOARD DIVIDERS IN EACH BOX TO KEEP THE BOTTLES FROM CONTACTING EACH OTHER DURING TRANSIT.  THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS IN THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX AND PLACED IT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED IT ON TO ITS DESTINATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERTY MARKED AND LABELED.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0128. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  (HOWEVER, IT IS SO FAINTLY WRITTEN THAT IT WILL PROBABLY NOT BE VERY GOOD.)

THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOTICED DUE TO A STRONG ODOR WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED.  THIS PLASTIC TOOL BOX WAS NOT LABELED OR MARKED TO DECLARE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS AND THEIR WAS NO PAPERWORK ASSOCIATED WITH IT TO SUGGEST IT CONTAINED ANYTHING THAT WAS HAZARDOUS.  WHEN THE TOOLBOX WAS OPENED, 4 X .45 OZ GLASS BOTTLES OF FINGERNAIL POLISH WERE DISCOVERED INSIDE AND WERE LEAKING AROUND THE CLOSURES. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND I CONTACTED DAVE KING OF THE SEA/CASFO TO REPORT THIS INCIDENT.  THE 4 BOTTLES WERE REMOVED AND THE TOOL CHEST WAS ALLOWED TO BE DELIVERED WITH THE APPROVAL OF DAVE KING ON 6-15.

column168: PASSENGER (JERRY FELICITAS) CHECKED-IN A 5-GALLON PLASTIC BUCKET FILLED WITH TOOLS, 2 QUART SIZED PLASTIC BOTTLES OF UNMARKED LIQUID, 4 LARGE AEROSOL CANS OF ENAMEL PAINT, AND 4 SMALLER AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT CANS.  PAINT AND LIQUID SUBMITTED TO COUNTER CHECK-IN AGENT AT ALOHA AIRLINES AS UNDECLARED.  DURING HANDLING AND LOADING IN CARGO COMPARTMENT, ONE OF THE QUART BOTTLES OF LIQUID WAS PUNCTURED BY SHARP TOOL AND LEAKED OUT.  SPILL SPREAD ON FLOORING OF AIRCRAFT FORWARD PIT,  AND ONTO OTHER PASSENGER LUGGAGE.  AIRCRAFT PULLED OUT OF SERVICE FOR CLEANING, THEN RETURNED SERVICE.  FAA IN HONOLULU (ADAM SHANEDLING 808-836-8411) CONDUCTING ON-GOING INVESTIGATION AND SENT UN-IDENTIFIED SPILLED LIQUID TO LABORATORY FOR ANALYSIS.  A FEW DAYS LATER, ALOHA OBTAINED NAME OF PRODUCT (DOW CORNING 772 WATER REPELLENT) FROM FELICITAS, AND UPON RECEIPT OF MSDS, TENTATIVELY IDENTIFIED THE SPILL AS CONTAINING A CLASS 8 CORROSIVE LIQUID.

column168: DRIVER JERAD JOHNSON LEFT.  FARGO TERMINAL @ 9:30 A.M.  TO DEL. DET. LAKES ROUTE. DURING HIS ROUTE HE SECURED BARRELLS ONCE AGAIN @ GROVER LINDBERG THE DEL BEFORE ST. DRIVER THEN JUMPED UP INTO TRUCK TO SECURE THE BARRELL UPRIGHT, NOTICED THE LEAK AND CONTENTS SPILLING OUT, A SMALL FIRE STARTED, DRIVER PUT IT OUT AND RAN INTO ST. MARY'S  TO CALL 911.  HE THEN WENT BACK OUT TO THE TRLR AND NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF TRLR'S REAR DOOR.  HE THEN KEPT ON LOOKERS AWAY UNTIL THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES ARRIVED, INFORMED THEM THERE WAS HAZMAT AND HANDED OVER HIS PAPERWORK OF WHAT THE HAZMAT MATERIALS WERE.  SECUNING BARRELLS TO THE WALL W/STRAPS WOULD HOLD THEN IN PLACE.  IMPROVEMENTS ON PACKAGING SHOULD BE MADE BY HAVING PLASTIC BARRELLS INSERTED INTO A SECOND BARRELL THAT COULD BE MORE RESISTANT TO CONTACT.

CSXT TRAINMASTER GARY PERKINS AT CORDELE, GA, REPORTED GATX 80004, LD METHANOL, SLOSHED PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  BRAKEMAN, FJ PADGETT (ID# 157040) WAS SPLASHED ON HEAD, NECK & ARM.  HE WAS WASHED OFF QUICKLY  & WENT BACK TO WORK.  THE YARD CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, GA PACIFIC CORPORATION  & ASKED THEM TO RESPONED GA PACKFIC SENT A MAN OUT TO CHECK THE CAR.  HE FOUND THE MANWAY COVER WAS COCKED IP ON ONE OF THE SAEFTY BOLTS WITH A 1/2 TO 1 IN GAP UNDER THE MANWAY COVER.  HE LOOSENED ALL THE MANWAY BOLTS, REPSOSITONED THE MANWAY COVER & TIGHTENED THE BOLTS.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED AND CHECKED FOR LEAKAGE.  THE LEAK WAS REPAIRED.  MR. PERKINGS STATED MR. PADGETT COMPLAINED OF SOME DIZZINESS AFTER BEING OUT IN THE SUN.  HE FELT BETTER WHEN HE WAS BROUGHT INDOORS.  MR. PADGETT WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTION.  THE HOSPITAL RAN SEVERAL TESTS ON MR. PADGETT, ALL OF WHICH WERE NEGATIVE.  BUT BECAUSE ONE TEST HAD TO BE SENT OUT, THE DOCTOR REQUIRED MR PADGETT STAY AT THE HOSPITAL UNTIL THE RESULTS WERE RECEIVED.  ON 6/27/00 IT WAS REPORTED ALL TEST CAME BACK NEGATIVE.  THE DOCTOR TOLD ME. PADGETT TO TAKE 4 DAYS OFF.  ON 7/5 MR. PADGETT WENT BACK TO WORK WITH NO APPARENT PROBLEMS.

FILE 2050 F&D, SHPR: TNT EXPRESS WORLDWIDE, AWB #18180284214 PFW. ON 06/07/00 AT 0333, A SMOKING PACKAGE, WITH AN ODOR OF GUNPOWDER, WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING "A" OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  THIS PACKAGE WAS REPORTED BY SORT SUPERVISOR BRENDA PENDLETON, AND A SMALL AREA WAS BEING EVACUATED, AS A PRECAUTION, AT THE TIME OF HER CALL.  DURING THIS CALL, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, TAMARA A. RAMIREZ, NOTIFIED ABX ARFF (AIR RESCUE & FIRE FIGHTERS)  OF THE PACKAGE AND THE LOCATION, VIA PHONE.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS, CECILIA HICKEY, TIMOTHY HINES, AND DONNA RESOR RESPONDED TO THIS PACKAGE, AS WELL AS HAZ MAT AREA MANAGER JAMES CURTIS, AND HAZMAT SORT SUPERVISOR KENNETH HAAG. ARFF SPECIALIST, MICKEY FRIEND, DARREN BROWN, RICHARD TARR, ROBIN STRONG, AND STEVE GAREN RESPONDED AS WELL.  UPON HAZMAT ARRIVAL, THE EMPLOYEE WHO NOTICED THE PACKAGE SMOKING, STATED THAT HE HEARD A CRACKING AND POPPING SOUND AFTER HE LOADED THIS PACKAGE INTO THE OUTBOUND "C" CONTAINER.  HE THEN NOTICED A LOT OF SMOKE COMING FROM THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION.  THE SORTER THEN REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE "C" CONTAINER AND HE SAID HE HEARD MORE CRACKING AND POPPING THAT HE DESCRIBED AS FIREWORKS GOING OFF IN RAPID SUCCESSION.  UPON ARFF ARRIVAL, THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS REMOVED BY TWO ARFF SPECIALIST, FROM "A" BUILDING TO THE CENTER OF GATE MAINTENANCE, VIA CUSHMAN, BY ARFF SPECIALIST MICKEY FRIEND.  ARFF THEN SATURATED THE BOX WITH WATER.  ONCE THE FIRE WAS OUT, AN INVESTIGATION OF THE CONTENTS BEGAN.  UPON THE INVESTIGATION A SMALL BURNT FIBERBOARD BOX WAS FOUND INSIDE.  A SMALL PORTION OF THE BURNT FIBERBOARD BOX STATED, STARTING PISTON CAPS- FIREWORKS TYPE "D" -1.4S UN 0337 -CONTAINS 0.07gx100=  (OBSCURED)- NOT LIABLE TO EXPLODE (OBSCURED) WARNING:  EXPLOSIVE ARTICLE, HANDLE WITH CARE. ABRASION AND IMPACT IS PROHIBITED. KEEP IN DRY PLACE AND TEMPERATURE NO MORE THAN 100 C. USED BY CHILDREN PROHIBITED. KEEP IN POCKET PROHIBITED. THE FIRE DESTROYED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE SMALL FIBERBOARD BOX.. THERE WERE ALSO NUMEROUS MISCELLANEOUS PARTY FAVORS IN THIS PACKAGE. THIS WAS A 1 OF 4 PIECE SHIPMENT.  THE OTHER THREE REMAINING PIECES WERE CAPTURED AT THE OUTBOUND STATION IN NEW YORK.  AT THE TIME OF THE AIRCRAFT DEPARTURE, THIS WAS NOT KNOWN TO BE A FOUR PIECE SHIPMENT.  BY THE TIME THIS WAS ABLE TO BE INVESTIGATED, THE AIRCRAFT HAD ALREADY DEPARTED.  A MESSAGE WAS SENT, VIA EMAIL, TO THE NEW YORK STATION ASKING THEM TO HOLD THE REMANING 3 PIECES FOR AN FAA AGENT TO INVESTIGATE.  HAZMAT AREA MANAGER JAMES CURTIS REQUESTED THAT THE FAA COME AND INVESTIGATE THIS SHIPMENT LATER IN THE A.M.  FAA SPECIAL AGENT JOHN BOCKIUS ARRIVED THAT A.M. AND INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT.  THE NEW YORK STATION NOTIFIED ILN HAZMAT, VIA EMAIL, AND LET US KNOW THAT THE REMAINING 3 PIECES WERE CAPTURED AND HAD BEEN INVESTIGATED BY FAA SPECIAL AGENT GEORGE MARTINEZ. ACCORDING TO PATRICK JOHNSON, OF THE NEW YORK STATION, AGENT MARTINEZ TOOK POSSESSION OF
