FILE: 2069D, SHIPPER:  TNT SKYPACK, AWB# LIQ 17051981914 MHT 06/20/2000 AT 0215 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING D BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT:  ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS ELWOOD BOHI AND MIRANDA SOUTH DONE PROPER PERSONEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX LOCATED ON THE CATWALK AREA.  THIS BOX WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX FROM THE CATWALK THAT WAS EMITTING THE ODOR AND BEGAN INSPECTION.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING ITEMS:  17 - GLASS SPRAY PUMP BOTTLES AT 3.5 OZ. EACH OF PERFUMERY PRODUCTS LISTED ON THE LABEL AREA AS FLAMMABLE.  THERE WERE 2 BOTTLES BROKEN AT A TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCTS, THIS WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  THE OTHER ITEMS IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE NON REGULATED MATERIALS.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX AND PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED BOX INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT SORT AREA SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THERE WERE 3 EMPLOYEES WHO NOTICED THE ODOR, THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND THEY RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED FOR THESE EMPLOYEES.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR TO SCENE 0237.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS HEADING SOUTH ON ROUTE 8 IN CHERRY TREE, PENNSYLVANIA WHEN HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE WHILE ATTEMPTING TO NEGOTIATE A BEND.  THE DRIVER WAS ROUTE FROM UNITED REFINING COMPANY IN WARREN, PENNSYLVANIA TO KWIK FILL TRUCK STOP IN HARRISVILLE, PENNSYLVANIA WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  AFTER LOSING CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, OUR TRUCK ENTERED A WOODED AREA ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD.  AT THIS POINT, THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER UNCOUPLED LEAVING THE TRACTOR WEDGED BETWEEN TWO TREES AND THE TRAILER OVERTURNED.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 A.M.  I, ROBERT MCCONNELL, WAS NOTIFIED AROUND 6:20 A.M.  I DISPATCHED COMPANY REPRESENTATIVES TO THE SCENE AS WELL AS D.G.D ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  ROBERT FRENZ, THE OWNER OF THE COMPANY, WAS ON THE SCENE AT 8:35 A.M. AND D.G.D ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AT 9:30 A.M. TO OVERSEE THE CLEANUP OF SPILLED PRODUCT AND HANDLE THE TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE WRECKED TRAILER TO A SECOND TRAILER.  PRIOR TO THE CLEANUP CREW AND COMPANY REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVING, I SPOKE WITH TROOPER RITCHIE OF THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE, SENECA BARRACKS AT 7:40 A.M.  TROOPER RICHIE INFORMED ME THAT THE ONLY SPILLAGE WAS FROM A FUEL TANK ON THE TRACTOR, WHICH HAD SPLIT IN THE ACCIDENT, AND THE TRAILER WAS STILL SEALED.  THE TRAILER NEVER BEGAN TO LEAK UNTIL A BELLY VALVE WAS REMOVED TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE COMPARTMENT.  REMOVAL OF THIS VALVE CAUSED AN APPARENT RELEASE OF PRESSURE AND THE DOME LID BEGAN TO LEAK.  TOTAL ESTIMATED LOSS FROM THE TRAILER WAS APPROXIMATELY 800 GALLONS.  ALL CLEANUP WAS HANDLED UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF D.G.D ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC; 500 COBHAM PARK RD; WARREN, PA 16365. AFTER A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT, THE DRIVER WAS REPRIMANDED.

THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A METAL CAN WITH A CAPACITY OF ONE GALLON.  THE LID SEAL ON THE CAN HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  AN MSDS SHEET FOR THE PRODUCT WAS REQUESTED AND OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER OF THE MATERIAL.  INFORMATION ON THIS DOCUMENT CLEARLY INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL MET THE DEFINITION OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THERE F.A.A.  FOR INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT WILLIAM BARTANOWICZ/FAA/SAT/CAFSO AT 12:10(CST) ON 06/28/2000.  ADDENDUM THIS SHIPMENT WAS BEING RETURNED TO REDSTONE KITCHEN & BATH IN DALLAS FROM THE RECIPIENT IN BOERNE, TX.  THE INITIAL SHIPMENT OF WAS MADE TO THE ORIGINAL RECIPIENT(BOB BRIEEFENGA) IN ERROR AND WAS BEING RETURNED WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED AND THE DISCREPANCY DISCOVERED.

THE CAPS WERE LOOSE, ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED WE DETERMINED THE CONTENTS.  THE SHIPPER CONFIRMED THE CONTENTS.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED IN ATLANTA,  I SPOKE TO FRED INTRATOR & LYNN LEONARD.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS. LABELING. SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column168: WHILE OUR DRIVER, ROGER LAYNE, WAS UNLOADING PROPANE INTO A STORAGE TANK AT VEGAS PROPANE, THE RELIEF VALVE ON THE COMPRESSOR STARTED TO RELEASE FUEL INTO THE AIR.  THE PROPANE TRAVELED UP INTO THE AIR. THE PROPANE TRAVELED UP INTO THE ENGINE CAUSING IT TO REV UP.  ROGER HEARD THE ENGINE, RAN AROUND THE TRUCK, GOT UP INTO THE CAB OF THE TRUCK TO SHUT OFF ENGINE WHEN THE FUEL IGNITED.  ROGER WAS BURNED WITH 2ND DEGREE BURNS TO 80% OF HIS BODY.  AFTER HAVING EVALUATED THIS INCIDENT, HURT'S IS CHARGING THE DIRECTION OF ALL OR OUR RELIEF VALVES ON OUR COMPRESSORS.  WE ARE ALSO ADDING TO EACH TRUCK A SHUTOFF SWITCH THAT WILL BE LOCATED BY THE COMPRESSOR H IS OUR HOPE THAT PERFORMING THESE TWO SAFETY ITEMS PRECAUTIONS WILL ELIMINATE THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH AN ACCIDENT HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

ON THURSDAY, 6/6/2000 AT ABOUT 1210 HOURS TANK CAR RAIX 2703 WAS OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING WHILE BEING HANDLED IN ROUTINE OPERATIONS AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILYARD AT LIVONIA, LA.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS OBSERVED DRIPPING FROM THE TOP AND EVAPORATING AS IT STREAMED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED INTO THE HAZ/MAT TRACK AT WHICH TIME RAIL OPERATIONS WERE CURTAILED ON THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD.  MR. PAUL PERSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, UPRR SAN ANTONIO WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRANGED FOR NOTIFICATION AND RESPONSE BY UNION CARBIDE PERSONNEL AND TOM ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, UPRR LIVONIA. ROBINSON CONTACTED MR. TOMMY MCGEHEE AND MR. LAYTON DUFRENE OF UNION CARBIDE AT THE SCENE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM THREADS WHERE THE LIQUID VALVE MOUNTS ONTO THE EDUCATION PIPE. ALSO, INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE TANK HAD 15.5 INCHES OF OUTAGE. THE THREADS WERE REDRESSED AND THE VALVE SECURED.  THE CAR WAS HELD OVER THE PANS FOR 24 HOURS TO ASSURE NO FURTHER LEAKAGE, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY RICHARD TUFTS WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC DISPATCHER, SHERRY, THAT A TANKCAR WAS VENTING AT INA, IL. MANAGER TUFTS TALKED WITH THE TRAIN DISPATCHER AND WITH MTO DAVID BRICKNER AND AUTHORIZED THE CAR TO BE MOVED INTO THE YARD AT SALEM TO BE INSPECTED BY MANAGER TUFTS.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CAR, MANAGER TUFTS DISCUSSED THE SITUATION WITH SHIPPER, AIR LIQUID, JOE CACCIOTTI AND DECIDED TO ATTEMPT TO RESEAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE CAR CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 23 LBS OF PRESSURE AND THE SAFETY VALVE WAS ALLOWING VAPOR TO ESCAPE.  MANAGER TUFTS ATTEMPTED SUCCESSFULLY TO RESEAT THE VALVE AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

STOW AWAY FROM FOODSTUFFS- SELF CONTAINED WAS FOUND ON PD-9.  PROPER PPE WAS WORN DECISION TREE AND STOW AWAY FROM FOODSTUFFS RESPONSE SHEET WERE CONSULTED.  AFFECTED MATERIAL WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM REMAINDER WAS RTS IN SALVAGE DRUM.

ROADWAY TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AT SIOUX FALLS CARTAGE FACILITY IN SIOUX FALLS. THE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AND WAS HELD IN SIOUX FALLS. WE CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE AND TOLD HIM IT WAS LEAKING AND HE REFUSED IT OVER THE PHONE. WE CALLED ROADWAY IN OMAHA AND THEY SENT US A RECOVERY DRUM AND WE RETURNED IT TO ROADWAY. WE ASKED THEM TO USE MORE DUNNAGE TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS FOR CLEAN UP WE PUT DOWN FLOOR DRY AND THEN ALLOWED EVERYTHING TO DRY BEFORE USING TRAILER.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AND AN EMPLOYEE SPLASHED BY THE PRODUCT. DEVELOPED THE ENGINEER WAS OPERATING LOCOMOTIVE SP 4814 MAKING A MOVE WITHIN YARD LIMITS, EAST YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, CALIFORNIA. WHILE THE LOCOMOTIVE WAS STOPPED, ANOTHER TRAIN PULLED ALONG SIDE ON AN ADJACENT TRACK, AND WHILE STOPPING THE TRAIN, LIQUID FROM THE ABOVE TANK CAR SPRAYED THE STOPPED LOCOMOTIVE AND ENGINEER. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY. THE MANWAY COVER SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE IN THE FOLLOWING ORDER: ( FROM CLOCKWISE POSITION) # 1: LOOSE ONE FULL TURN; #2: LOOSE ONE FULL TURN; #3: LOOSE ONE HALF TURN; #4: LOOSE HALF TURN; #5: LOOSE ONE HALF TURN; #6: LOOSE ONE HALF TURN; #7: LOOSE ONE HALF TURN; #8: LOOSE ONE FULL TURN. ALL THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE PROPERLY TIGHTENED. IT APPEARS THAT WHEN THE INBOUND TRAIN STOPPED THE TANK CAR NEXT TO THE LOCOMOTIVE, THE LIQUID SURGE IN THE CAR BY PASSED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE, SPRAYING THE ADJACENT LOCOMOTIVE AND ENGINEER. INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR SHOWED SIGNS OF MINIMAL PRODUCT ON THE TOP SURFACE OF THE CAR. THE LOCOMOTIVE HAD SPOTTING OF THE PRODUCT ALL ALONG THE RIGHT FRONT SIDE, WHERE THE ENGINEER IS LOCATED. THE ENGINEER WASHED THE PRODUCT FROM HIS FACE AND HANDS, HOWEVER, DID NOT CHANGE HIS CLOTHING WHICH STILL CONTAINED PRODUCT RESIDUE. THE ENGINEER DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL TREATMENT, AND WAS SENT HOME TO REPLACE HIS CLOTHING. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER, FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ITS PERSONNEL REPORTING A LEAKING TRAILER AT THE EAST YARD, LOS ANGELES. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD AND LOCATED THE ABOVE TRAILER IN PARKING AREA GREEN 302. A SMALL POOL ( LESS THAN 2 GALLONS) OF PRODUCT HAD ACCUMULATED ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE MIDSHIP AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOORING. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS TO INSPECT THE LADING, OBSERVED SEVERAL 55 GALLON OVER PACK DRUMS CLOSE TO THE REAR DOORS. THERE WAS A 3-4 FOOT VOID BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE REAR DOORS. THE ONLY CONTAINMENT USED WAS A SCRAP PIECE OF 2X4 LUMBER NAILED TO THE FLOOR, AND A SINGLE METAL BAND AROUND THE LAST 4 OVER PACKED DRUMS. INSPECTION OF THE LADING FOUND THE ENTIRE LOAD TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS AND A TOTAL OF 10 OVER PACKED DRUMS. ALL OF THE DRUMS SHOWED SEVERE SIGNS OF DISTRESS, AND THERE WAS NO RHYME OR REASON TO THE LOADING PATTERN. IT WAS APPARENT THE DRUMS HAD BEEN LOADED IN THIS CONDITION, AS THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE WOULD NOT OCCUR UNDER NORMAL CONDITIONS, EVEN IF THE ENTIRE LOAD HAS SHIFTED. ONE DRUM IN THE CENTER OF THE LOAD WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE DRUM. ABSORBENT WAS PLACED AROUND THE DRUM TO KEEP THE PRODUCT FROM SPREADING. THE PRODUCT ON THE PAVEMENT WAS CLEANED UP, BAGGED, AND PLACED INTO THE TRAILER FOR SECUREMENT. A CHECK WITH MOL DEVELOPED THEY HAD NO RECORD OF THIS TRAILER. A CALL TO THE UP DAMAGE PREVENTION GROUP DEVELOPED THIS PRODUCT HAD BEEN TRANSLOADED FROM CONTAINER MOGU 256331, THAT HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A KANSAS DERAILMENT ON 5-14. THE DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO THE TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED TO KANSAS CITY FOR RELOADING AND RETURN TO THE MANUFACTURER. PRIOR TO THE LADING BEING TRANSFERED IN KANSAS CITY,THE BILLING FROM THE  DERAILED CONTAINER WAS SWITCHED OVER TO THE TRAILER, AND IT WAS SCHEDULED ON A TRAIN TO LOS ANGELES. DAMAGE PREVENTION IS CURRENTLY WORKING ON A DISPOSITION FOR THIS FREIGHT.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT COLTON, CALIFORNIA. DEVELOPED THE CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING IN THE RECEIVING YARD BY THE CAR DEPARTMENT AS THEY WERE INSPECTING THE INBOUND TRAIN ON TRACK #204. A SMALL TRAIL OF PRODUCT WAS TRICKLING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR ADJACENT TO THE SIDE MOUNTED LADDER, AND LESS THAN 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ACCUMULATED ON THE GROUND BELOW THE CAR. MANAGER COOPER HAD TEC RESPOND TO INSPECT THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS FROM THE CLOSURE CAP ON THE TOP LIQUID LINE. ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN, AND THEN REMOVE THE CAP MEET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS, AS THE CAP APPEARED TO BE FROZEN IN PLACE. THE AIR LINE WAS OPENED TO RELIEVED THE INTERNAL PRESSURE ON THE CAR, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. ARRANGEMENT WERE MADE TO MOVE THE CAR TO THE ONE SPOT REPAIR TRACK, ALONG WITH TANK CAR ASTX 5133. ASTX5133 WAS THE TRAILING TANK CAR BEHIND THE ASTX 5139 TANK CAR, AND WAS PARTIALLY COVERED WITH PRODUCT THAT SPRAYED ON IT WHILE IN TRANSIT. ONCE THE CARS WERE IN PLACE AT THE ONE SPOT, THE CAP ON THE LIQUID LINE WAS MUSCLED OFF. THE PIPE THREADS APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE THREADS AND THE CAP REINSTALLED. BOTH CARS WERE DECONED AND CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE. THE CARS WERE MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO INSURE PROPER CLOSURE, AND THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS IN PARKING AREA GREEN # 110, AND A SMALL AMOUT ( LESS THAN 1 GALLON) OF PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED FROM THE CENTER AREA OF THE CONTAINER FLOORING ONTO THE PAVEMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK, WHERE INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LADING TO CONSIST OF DOUBLE STACKED 55 GALLON DRUMS. THE DRUMS WERE SECURED WITH TY GARD AT THE REAR DOOR AREA, HOWEVER, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE TOP AND BOTTOM TIRES OF DRUMS WERE NOT DOUBLE BAYED WITH THE TY GARD MATERIAL. THIS IS NOT RECOMMENDED, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD OF SECUREMENT FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON THE RAIL. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MITSUI, WHO PROVIDED THEIR SHIPPER, C. H. ROBINSON IN MICHIGAN. ROBINSON PROVIDED A CONTACT FOR THEIR SHIPPER, FILBOND, WHO WAS ADVISED THE LADING WOULD HAVE TO BE REMOVED IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM(S). ONCE THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED, A SINGLE DRUM , LOCATED 6 ROWS FROM THE REAR DOOR, ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER SIDEWALL, WAS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE DRUM HAD BEEN PLACED AGAINST THE SIDEWALL AND THE BOTTOM CHIME RUBBED AGAINST THE BOTTOM FRAME OF THE CONTAINER. THE FLOORING IS SLIGHTLY RECESSED WHICH LEAVES A 1/8 INCH ELEVATION BETWEEN THE FLOOR AND THE SIDEWALL FLOOR FRAME. THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM RUBBED AGAINST THE FLOOR FRAME DURING TRANSIT, WHICH CREATED A SMALL CRACK FOR THE PRODUCT TO PASS THROUGH. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND THE REMOVED DRUMS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE DAMAGED DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR REQUEST. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE CAR FOREMAN, DEPARTURE YARD, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO COLTON, AND IN COMPANY WITH CAR FOREMAN MONTOYA, INSPECTED THE ABOVE TANK CAR ON DEPARTURE TRACK #314. INSPECTION NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT A RATE OF 8-10 DROPS PER MINUTE. INSPECTION OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE FLANGE WHERE THE BOTTOM OUTLET ATTACHES TO THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TANK CAR. ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE 8 FLANGE BOLTS SLOWED THE LEAK TO 1-2 DROPS PER MINUTE, BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL IN COMPLETELY SECURING THE LEAK IT APPEARED THE FLANGE GASKET WAS DETERIORATED. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MR. BOYER DRUM, CLARIANT, CHARLOTTE, NORTH CAROLINA, WHO WAS ADVISED THE PRODUCT WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERED. MR. DRUM MADE ARRANGEMENT WITH CELTRANS, THE CAR OWNER, TO HAVE QUALITY CARRIERS REMOVE THE PRODUCT, AND TRANSPORT THE PRODUCT IN TRUCKS TO THE SHIPPER FOR DELIVERY. A PAIL WAS SECURED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET TO CAPTURE ANY ADDITIONAL DRIPPAGE, AND THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE ONE SPOT, WERE IT WAS ACCESSIBLE FOR OFF LOADING. TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED ON 6-10-00, AND THE CAR WAS RELASED FOR MOVEMENT TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR INSPECTION. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER JACK GIACONA WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT A DERAILMENT AT THE UNION PACIFIC YARD IN ANGLETON, TX DURING THE RERAILING PROCESS, TANK CAR DBCX 9800 LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT FROM THE THERMOMETER WELL.  BASF COMPANY'S HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND SECURED THE FITTING.

THE MISSING BOLT WAS REPLACED AND ALL LOOSE BOLTS TIGHTENED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 16:00 HRS.

column168: TRAILER CAME TO SAN ANTONIO CONWAY YARD ALREADY LEAKING. AFTER DETERMINING THAT THE SPILL WAS PAINT TO TRAILER WAS OPENED AND WE DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE MIDDLE. THE DRUM DID NOT HAVE PROTECTIVE DUNNAGE AROUND THE EXPOSED SIDES. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A PALLET BEING LOADED IN FROM OF THE DRUM AND THE FORKS EXTENDING PAST THE PALLET INTO THE DRUM THAT WAS NOT PROTECTED. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF PROPER DUNNAGE WAS USED TO PROTECT THE DRUM.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AN ALL-STAR TRANSPORT TANKER RAN OFF THE WEST SHOULDER OF THE SOUTH BOUND LANES OF INTERSTATE 55, APPROXIMATELY 4 MILES SOUTH OF BENTON, MISSOURI ON JUNE 11, 2000.  AS THE TRUCK RAN OFF THE SHOULDER, THE CARGO TANKER HIT A TREE, WHICH PENETRATED THE CARGO TANK.  THE TANKER THEN ROLLED OVER ON IT TOP, INTO A LOW WATER DITCH.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TRUCK (APPROXIMATELY 8,000 GALLONS OF 87 OCTANE GASOLINE) RELEASED INTO THE DITCH.  MISSOURI HIGHWAY PATROL AND SCOTT COUNTY FIRE DISTRICT WERE FIRST TO RESPOND.  THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED.  SCOTT COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, OF BENTON, MISSOURI, MOBILIZED HEAVY EQUIPMENT TO RESPOND TO THE RELEASE.  THE SOUTH BOUND LANES OF INTERSTATE 55 WERE CLOSED, THE DITCH WAS BERMED UP TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  DORRIS PLUMBING, OF POPLAR BLUFF, MISSOURI, WAS CALLED IN TO PROVIDE PRODUCT RECOVERY SERVICES.  SMITH & COMPANY, OF POPLAR BLUFF, MISSOURI, WAS RETAINED TO PROVIDE ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTING SERVICES. APPROXIMATELY 1,400 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED BY DORRIS PLUMBING. THE WASTE PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY INTER-RAIL SYSTEMS, IF CAPE GIRARDEAU, MISSOURI.  APPROXIMATELY 2,445 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND HAULED TO LEMONS LANDFILL, OF DEXTER, MISSOURI.  THE SITE WAS BROUGHT BACK TO PRE-EXCAVATION GRADE AND SEEDED ACCORDING TO MODOT'S REQUIREMENTS.  SMITH & COMPANY CONDUCTED A LIMITED SITE CHARACTERIZATION OF THE GROUND WATER.  THREE GROUND WATER MONITORING WELLS WERE INSTALLED TO DELINEATE THE CONTAMINATION PLUME.  AFTER ONE YEAR OF QUARTERLY GROUND WATER MONITORING, MDNR REQUIRED NO FURTHER ACTION FOR THE REMEDIATION OF THE SITE.
